ervatism]]<br />[[Christian democracy]]<br />[[Social conservatism]]\n|predecessor = \n|position = [[Centrist|Centre]] to [[centre-right]]\n|headquarters = NLIC Building, Ayala Avenue, Makati City\n|international = \n|merger = \n|split = [[Lakas Kampi CMD]]\n|colors = {{Color box|{{National Unity Party (Philippines)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Green]]\n|senate_seats = {{Composition bar|0|24|hex=#104a21}}\n|house_seats = {{Composition bar|41|303|hex=#104a21}}\n|governorships = {{Composition bar|9|81|hex=#104a21}}\n|vice_governorships = {{Composition bar|4|81|hex=#104a21}}\n|provincial_boards = {{Composition bar|74|1006|hex=#125a21}}\n|national =[[Team PNoy]] (2013) <br> [[Coalition For Change (Philippines)|Coalition For Change]] (2016-Incumbent)\n|website = [http://www.nup.org.ph/ NUP.org.ph]\n}}\n\n'''National Unity Party''' ('''NUP''') is a political party in the [[Philippines]]. The party was formed by former members of [[Lakas Kampi CMD]] who broke away after internal discontent within the party. Since 2016, the party is part of the [[PDP\u2013Laban|PDP-LABAN]]-led coalition in the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|House of Representatives]], the [[Coalition for Change (Philippines)|Coalition for Change]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/135104-national-unity-party-nup-signs-agreement-pdp-laban|title=NUP seals alliance with PDP-Laban|work=Rappler|access-date=2018-07-22|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/788816/nup-dutertes-pdp-laban-formalize-alliance|title=NUP, Duterte\u2019s PDP-Laban formalize alliance|last=Ager|first=Maila|access-date=2018-07-22|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe party was accredited by the [[Commission of Elections]] as a national party in a resolution dated October 5, 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rosario|first=Ben|title=National Unity Party accredited|url=http://mb.com.ph/articles/340761/national-unity-party-accredited|accessdate=14 November 2011|newspaper=The Manila Bulletin|date=10 November 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406041239/http://mb.com.ph/articles/340761/national-unity-party-accredited|archivedate=6 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn September 26, 2012, the party held its first national convention where they announced support for [[Team PNoy]] for the [[2013 Philippine general election|2013 elections]], however most NUP members ultimately supported the [[United Nationalist Alliance]], especially Garcia.\n\n== Ideology and positions ==\nAccording to the party's constitution, NUP's principles include the following: [[Theism|belief in God]]; [[Sovereignty|sovereignty of the state]], national interest and democracy; [[social justice]] and responsibility; and [[Environmentalism|environmental awareness]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nup.org.ph/Constitutionbylaws|title=National Unity Party|website=nup.org.ph|access-date=2018-07-22}}</ref>\n\n* '''Chairman:''' [[Ronaldo Puno|Ronaldo V. Puno]]\n* '''Vice-Chairman for Local Government:''' Alberto Garcia\n* '''Vice-Chairman for Political Affairs:''' Hon. [[Isko Moreno Domagoso]], Mayor of Manila\n* '''Vice-Chairman for External Affairs:''' [[Romeo Acop]]\n* '''Vice-Chairman for Internal Affairs:''' Rep. [[Roberto Puno]], Deputy Speaker House of Representative, 1st District of Antipolo\n* '''National President:''' Rep. [[Elpidio Barzaga Jr.]], Lone District of Damarinas\n* '''Secretary-General:'''  Rep. [[Narciso Bravo Jr.]], 1st District Representative of Masbate\n* '''Treasurer:''' Rep. Gavini C. Pancho, 2nd District of Bulacan\n\n== List of party chairmen ==\n* Pablo P. Garcia (2011\u20132013)\n* Ronaldo Puno (2013\u2013present)\n\n==Elected members==\n===District Representatives===\n* Romeo M. Acop\n* Baby Aline Vargas-Alfonso\n* Franz Josef E. Alvarez\n* Magnolia C. Antonino\n* Jennifer A. Barzaga\n* Ma. Vida E. Bravo\n*Wilfredo S. Caminero\n* Fredenil H. Castro\n*Luisa L. Cuaresma\n* Leo Rafael M. Cueva\n* Juliet Marie D. Ferrer\n* Luis A. Ferrer IV\n* Suharto T. Mangudadatu\n* Alejandro Y. Mirasol\n* Evelyn P. Mellana\n* John Marvin \"Yul Servo\" S. Nieto\n* Edwin C. Ong\n* Gavini C. Pancho\n* Ma. Valentina G. Plaza\n* Ma. Cristina R. Puno\n* Rene L. Relampagos\n* Strike B. Revilla\n* Benhur L. Salimbangon\n* Edgar Mary S. Sarmiento\n* Lorna C. Silverio\n* Jose Antonio R. Sy-Alvarado\n* Joy S. Tambunting\n* Randolph S. Ting\n* Jerry R. Tre\u00f1as\n* Renato J. Unico, Jr.\n* Juliette T. Uy\n* Micaela S. Violago\n\n===Governors===\n* Ma. Jocelyn V. Bernos - Abra\n* Rhodora J. Cadiao - Antique\n* Roel R. Degamo - Negros Oriental\n* Albert Raymond S. Garcia - Bataan\n* Rashidin H. Matba - Tawi Tawi\n* Adolph Edward G. Plaza - Agusan Del Sur\n* Herminia M. Ramiro - Misamis Occidental\n* Daniel R. Fernando - Bulacan\n\n===Mayors===\n* Leopoldo \"Pol\" N. Bataoil - [[Lingayen, Pangasinan]]\n* Reynaldo San Pedro \u2013 [[San Jose del Monte City, Bulacan]]\n* Aldrin San Pedro \u2013 [[Muntinlupa City]]\n* [[Joet Garcia|Jose Enrique Garcia III]] \u2013 [[Balanga, Bataan]]\n* [[Gila Garcia]] \u2013 [[Dinalupihan, Bataan]]\n* [[Bartolome Ramos]] \u2013 [[Sta. Maria, Bulacan]]\n* Elpidio Barzaga Jr. \u2013 [[Dasmari\u00f1as, Cavite]]\n* Canuto \"Tito\" Oreta (\u2020) \u2013 [[Malabon City]]\n* Dr. Feliciano Legaspi, M.D. \u2013 [[Norzagaray, Bulacan]]\n*[[Isko Moreno]] - [[City of Manila]]\n* Luis \"Jon-Jon\" Ferrer IV \u2013 [[General Trias, Cavite]]\n* Maloney Samaco \u2013 [[Maasin City, Southern Leyte]]\n* Arnel Mendoza \u2013 [[Bustos, Bulacan]]\n* Patrick Meneses \u2013 [[Bulakan, Bulacan]]\n* Enrico Roque - [[Pandi, Bulacan]]\n* Jocell Vistan-Casaje \u2013 [[Plaridel, Bulacan]]\n* Philip Tan \u2013 [[Tangub, Misamis Occidental]]\n* Reynaldo \"Aldong\" Parojinog, Sr. \u2013 [[Ozamiz City, Misamis Occidental]]\n* Joselito \"Litoy\" Alega \u2013 [[San Francisco, Quezon]]\n* Michael Gutierrez \u2013 [[Lopez Jaena, Misamis Occidental]]\n* Jose G. Ardales \u2013 [[Victoria, Northern Samar]]\n* Ret. Col. Celso G. Regencia \u2013 [[Iligan, Lanao del Norte]]\n* Kim Lope \"Bobong\" A. Asis \u2013 [[Bayugan, Agusan del Sur]]\n* Engr. [[Ronnie Vicente Lagnada]] - [[Butuan]]\n* Stephen Alayon- [[Sigma, Capiz]]\n* [[Monico Puentevella]] - [[Bacolod City, Negros Occidental]]\n* John Geesnell \"Baba\" Lim Yap - [[Tagbilaran, Bohol]]\n* Roberto \"Bobby\" Sanchez - [[Lubang, Occidental Mindoro]]\n*Jerry P. Tre\u00f1as -  Iloilo City\n\n==Electoral History==\n===President===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Election\n! Number of votes\n! Share of votes\n! Outcome of election\n|-\n| [[2016 Philippine presidential election|2016]]\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| [[Rodrigo R. Duterte]]\n|}\n\n===Vice-President===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Election\n! Number of votes\n! Share of votes\n! Outcome of election\n|-\n| [[2016 Philippine presidential election|2016]]\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| [[Leni Robredo]]\n|}\n\n===Senate===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Election\n! Number of votes\n! Share of votes\n! Seats won\n! Seats after\n! Outcome of election\n|-\n| [[2013 Philippine Senate election|2013]]\n| Did Not Participate\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{Composition bar|0|12|hex={{National Unity Party (Philippines)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{Composition bar|0|24|hex={{National Unity Party (Philippines)/meta/color}}}}\n| [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal]]-led coalition\n|-\n| [[2016 Philippine Senate election|2016]]\n| Did Not Participate\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{Composition bar|0|12|hex={{National Unity Party (Philippines)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{Composition bar|0|24|hex={{National Unity Party (Philippines)/meta/color}}}}\n| [[PDP-Laban]]-led coalition\n|}\n\n===House of Representatives===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Election\n! Number of votes\n! Share of votes\n! Seats\n! Outcome of election\n|-\n|[[2013 Philippine House of Representatives elections|2013]]\n|2,394,631\n|8.68%\n|{{Composition bar|29|292|hex={{National Unity Party (Philippines)/meta/color}}}}\n| '''Split'''; [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal Party]]-led coalition, lost\n|-\n|[[2016 Philippine House of Representatives elections|2016]]\n|3,604,266\n|9.67%\n|{{Composition bar|23|297|hex={{National Unity Party (Philippines)/meta/color}}}}\n| [[PDP-Laban]]-led '''coalition'''\n|-\n|[[2019 Philippine House of Representatives elections|2019]]\n|3,852,909\n|9.59%\n|{{Composition bar|25|306|hex={{National Unity Party (Philippines)/meta/color}}}}\n| [[PDP-Laban]]-led '''coalition'''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.nup.org.ph/}}\n*{{Facebook|NationalUnityParty}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n{{Philippine political parties}}\n{{Philippines topics}}\n\n[[Category:Christian democratic parties in Asia]]\n[[Category:Conservative parties in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2011]]\n[[Category:Social conservative parties]]\n", "name_user": "Howard the Duck", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHouse of Representatives", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Unity_Party_(Philippines)"}
{"title_page": "Pamela S. Karlan", "text_new": "{{short description|American legal scholar}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Pamela Karlan\n| image = Pamela S. Karlan (49565892516) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Karlan at the [[Edmond J. Safra Center for Ethics]] in 2020\n| birth_name = Pamela Susan Karlan\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1959|1|1}}\n| birth_place = \n| nationality = [[Americans|American]]\n| education = [[Yale University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| occupation = American legal scholar\n| years_active = 1984\u2013present\n| partner = [[Viola Canales]]\n}}\n'''Pamela Susan Karlan''' (born February 1, 1959) is an American professor of law at [[Stanford Law School]]. A leading legal scholar on [[Voting rights in the United States|voting rights]] and political process, she served as U.S. Deputy Assistant Attorney General for Voting Rights in the [[United States Department of Justice Civil Division]] from 2014 to 2015.<ref>{{ cite news | last = Taylor | first = Stuart | title = An excellent Supreme Court shortlist | work = National Journal | publisher = [[Atlantic Media|Atlantic Media Company]] | url = http://www.nationaljournal.com/njmagazine/or_20100410_3801.php | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100412025442/http://www.nationaljournal.com/njmagazine/or_20100410_3801.php | archivedate = 2010-04-12 }}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nKarlan earned her B.A. degree in history from [[Yale University]] in 1980, as well as an M.A. degree in history and [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree in 1984.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web | title = Profile: Pamela S. Karlan | url = http://www.law.stanford.edu/directory/profile/32/ | publisher = Stanford Law School | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080605222907/http://www.law.stanford.edu/directory/profile/32/ | archivedate = 2008-06-05 }}</ref> At [[Yale Law School]], she served as an article and book reviews editor of the ''[[Yale Law Journal]]''.<ref name=\"cv\">{{cite web | last = Karlan | first = Pamela S. | title = CV | url = https://www-cdn.law.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/2015.KarlanCV.December1.pdf |accessdate = 22 January 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAfter graduation from law school, Karlan worked as a [[law clerk]] for former U.S. District Judge [[Abraham David Sofaer]] of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York|Southern District of New York]] from 1984 to 1985. She went on to clerk for [[U.S. Supreme Court Justice]] [[Harry Blackmun]] the following year. In a 1995 oral history with [[Harold Koh]], Blackmun revealed that his dissent in ''[[Bowers v. Hardwick]]'' had been written primarily by Karlan. He said that Karlan \"did a lot of very effective writing, and I owe a lot to her and her ability in getting that dissent out. She felt very strongly about it, and I think is correct in her approach to it. I think the dissent is correct.\"<ref>{{cite news | last = Volokh | first = Eugene | title = Saturday, April 23, 2005 | publisher = The Volokh Conspiracy: The Washington Post | date = 23 April 2005 | accessdate = 23 March 2015 | url = http://volokh.com/archives/archive_2005_04_17-2005_04_23.shtml#1114025448 }}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter her clerkships, Karlan worked as an assistant counsel at the [[NAACP]] [[NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund|Legal Defense and Educational Fund]] from 1986 to 1988.\n\nFrom 1988 to 1998, Karlan taught law at the [[University of Virginia]] [[University of Virginia School of Law|School of Law]], where she won the All-University Outstanding Teaching Award in 1995\u201396 and the [[State Council of Higher Education for Virginia]]'s Outstanding Faculty Award in 1997.<ref name=\"bio\" /> In 1998, Karlan joined the faculty of [[Stanford Law School]]. She is the school's Kenneth and Harle Montgomery Professor of [[Public interest law|Public Interest Law]]. In 2004, Karlan cofounded the Stanford Supreme Court Litigation [[Legal clinic|Clinic]], through which students litigate live cases before the [[U.S. Supreme Court]].<ref name=\"cv\" /> In 2002, Karlan won the school's prestigious John Bingham Hurlbut Award for Excellence in Teaching.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nKarlan has frequently commented on legal matters for ''[[PBS NewsHour]]''. During the disputed [[2000 United States presidential election|2000 presidential election]], she appeared regularly in the news media to discuss its comportment with constitutional law. In the aftermath of the election, Karlan, [[Samuel Issacharoff]], and [[Richard Pildes]] adapted two chapters from the law school casebook that they co-authored into a book entitled, ''When Elections Go Bad: The Law of Democracy and the Presidential Election of 2000''.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n\nOn December 4, 2019, Karlan\u2014alongside law professors [[Noah Feldman]], [[Michael Gerhardt]], and [[Jonathan Turley]]\u2014testified before the House Judiciary Committee regarding the constitutional grounds for presidential impeachment in the [[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump|Impeachment inquiry of President Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"2019 - New York Times - Who Is\">{{cite news |last1=Fadulu |first1=Lola |title=Who Is Pamela Karlan? Legal Leader Committed to Progressive Causes |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/04/us/politics/pamela-karlan.html |work=The New York Times |date=4 December 2019}}</ref> She made a controversial statement delivered during the December 2019, impeachment hearing of President Trump, \u201cContrary to what President Trump has said, Article 2 [of the Constitution] does not give him the power to do anything he wants,\u201d testified Pamela Karlan, a professor at Stanford Law School. \u201cThe Constitution says there can be no titles of nobility, so while the president can name his son Barron, he can\u2019t make him a baron.\u201d Karlan apologized afterward. <ref>C-Span: Professor Pamela Karlan references Barron Trump and later apologizes for it. Dec 4, 2019. </ref>  \n\nKarlan is a member of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]], the [[American Academy of Appellate Lawyers]], and the [[American Law Institute]].<ref name=\"bio\"/>\n\n=== Public service ===\nIn 2003, she was appointed to the [[California Fair Political Practices Commission]] by [[California State Controller|Controller]] [[Steve Westly]]. Until 2005, she served as commissioner to help implement and enforce [[California]]\u2019s [[Campaign finance in the United States|campaign finance]], [[Lobbying in the United States|lobbying]], and [[conflict of interest]] laws.<ref name=\"cv\" />\n\nOn December 20, 2013, Karlan was appointed by the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] to serve as the U.S. Deputy Assistant Attorney General for [[Voting rights in the United States|Voting Rights]] in the [[United States Department of Justice Civil Rights Division]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Gerstein | first = Josh | title = Karlan to take Justice Department voting rights post | url = http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2013/12/karlan-to-take-justice-department-voting-rights-post-180045.html?hp=l10 | date = 20 December 2013 | accessdate = 23 March 2015 | work = [[Politico|The Politico]] | publisher = Capitol News Company }}</ref> The position did not require confirmation by the [[U.S. Senate]]. Karlan took up her post on January 13, 2014, and served for one year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/person/?pamelakarlan|title=Pamela S. Karlan {{!}} C-SPAN.org|website=www.c-span.org|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Gregg | first = Remington | title = HRC Blog: Pamela Karlan takes helm as Deputy Assistant Attorney General in DOJ Civil Rights Division | website = hrc.org | publisher = Human Rights Campaign | url = http://www.hrc.org/blog/entry/pamela-karlan-take-helm-as-deputy-assistant-attorney-general-in-doj-civil-r | date = 13 January 2014 | accessdate = 23 March 2014 }}</ref> For her work in implementing the Supreme Court decision in ''[[United States v. Windsor]]'', she received the Attorney General\u2019s Award for Exceptional Service, the DOJ's highest award for employee performance.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|title=Pamela S. Karlan Biography|url=https://law.stanford.edu/directory/pamela-s-karlan/|website=Stanford Law School|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThroughout her career, Karlan has been an advocate before the [[U.S. Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite news |first= Adam |last= Liptak | title = So, guy walks up to the bar, and Scalia says... | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/31/politics/31mirth.html | work = [[The New York Times]] | date = 31 December 2005 }}</ref> She was mentioned as [[Barack Obama Supreme Court candidates|a potential candidate]] to replace Supreme Court Justice [[David Souter]] when he retired in 2009.<ref>{{cite news | title = Articles about Pamela S. Karlan | work = [[The New York Times]] | url = http://topics.nytimes.com/topics/reference/timestopics/people/k/pamela_s_karlan/index.html  }}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nPeter Baker, a New York Times political writer, described the subject as \"a full-throated, unapologetic liberal torchbearer\".<ref>Baker, Peter. (25 May 2009). \"Favorites of Left Don\u2019t Make Obama\u2019s Court List\". [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/26/us/politics/26court.html New York Times website] Retrieved 1 February 2020.</ref>  Karlan has said that the United States should help Ukraine fight Russia so that the United States does not have to fight Russia on its own territory.<ref>{{cite news |first= Tim |last= Hains | title = Professor Karlan: Ukraine Is Important \"So We Can Fight The Russians There And We Don't Have To Fight Them Here\" | url = https://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2019/12/04/professor_karlan_ukraine_is_important_so_we_can_fight_the_russians_there_and_we_dont_have_to_fight_them_here.html | work = [[RealClearPolitics]] | date = 4 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKarlan told ''[[The Politico|Politico]]'' in 2009, \"It's no secret at all that I'm counted among the [[LGBT]] crowd\".<ref name=polico_20090505>{{cite news |first=Josh |last=Gerstein | work = [[The Politico]] |url= http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0509/22106.html |title=Groups push for first gay Supreme Court justice |date=5 May 2009 |accessdate=12 April 2010 | publisher = Capitol News Company}}</ref> She has described herself as an example of \"snarky, [[bisexual]], Jewish women\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acslaw.org/expertforum/stanford-law-professor-pam-karlan-concludes-2006-acs-national-convention/|title=American Constitution Society Blog: Stanford Law Professor Pam Karlan concludes 2006 ACS National Convention|last=|first=|date=22 June 2006|website=|publisher=American Constitution Society for Law and Policy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref> Her partner is writer [[Viola Canales]].<ref>{{cite news  |first= Esselink |last= Jean Ann | title = On our radar \u2013 An overdue thank you To Pamela Karlan | work = The New Civil Rights Movement | url = http://www.thenewcivilrightsmovement.com/on-our-radar-an-overdue-thank-you-to-pamela-karlan/news/2013/12/29/80872 | date = 29 December 2013 | accessdate =23 March 2015  }}</ref>\n\n==Works and publications==\n===Selected books===\n* {{cite book |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela S. |title=A Constitution for All Times |date=2013 |publisher=MIT Press |location=Cambridge, MA |isbn=978-0-262-01989-7 |oclc=863038741|jstor=j.ctt9qf8bs }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Issacharoff |first1=Samuel |last2=Karlan |first2=Pamela S. |last3=Pildes |first3=Richard H. |last4=Persily |first4=Nathan |title=The Law of Democracy: Legal Structure of the Political Process |date=2016 |publisher=Foundation Pres |location=St. Paul, MN |isbn=9781628102253 |edition=5th |url=http://www.thelawofdemocracy.com/ |oclc=956640376}}\n\n===Selected journals===\n* {{cite journal |last1=Brennan |first1=William J. |last2=Ginsburg |first2=Ruth Bader |last3=Arnold |first3=Richard S. |last4=Griswold |first4=Erwin N. |last5=Karlan |first5=Pamela S. |last6=Koh |first6=Harold Hongju |title=A Tribute to Justice Harry A. Blackmun |journal=Harvard Law Review |date=1994 |volume=108 |issue=1 |pages=163\u20138 |issn=0017-811X |jstor=1341989|pmid=3333213 }}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela S. |title=The Supreme Court \u2013 Comments. Electing Judges, Judging Elections, and the Lessons of Caperton |journal=Harvard Law Review |date=November 2009 |volume=123 |issue=1 |pages=80\u2013103 |url=https://harvardlawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/karlan09.pdf |issn=0017-811X |oclc=472051099}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela |title=Henry J. Miller Lecture Series: Old Reasons, New Reasons, No Reasons |journal=Georgia State University Law Review |date=Summer 2011 |volume=27 |issue=4 |url= https://readingroom.law.gsu.edu/gsulr/vol27/iss4/2/ |issn=8755-6847 |oclc=8092032473}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela S. |title=In Memoriam: William J. Stuntz |journal=Harvard Law Review |date=June 2011 |volume=124 |issue=8 |pages=1841\u20131843 |url=https://harvardlawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/vol124_stuntz_tribute.pdf}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela |title=The Swing Justice: Reflections on the Career of Justice Anthony Kennedy. Panel 1: Abortion and Gay Rights |journal=Georgia State University Law Review |date=Spring 2019 |volume=35 |issue=5 (Supplement) |pages=871\u2013905 |url= https://readingroom.law.gsu.edu/gsulr/vol35/iss5/1/ |issn=8755-6847 |oclc=1101178994}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://law.stanford.edu/directory/pamela-s-karlan/ Pamela S. Karlan] at [[Stanford University Law School]]\n* {{C-SPAN|Pamela Karlan}}\n* [https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/cf_dev/AbsByAuth.cfm?per_id=136810 Pamela S. Karlan] at [[Social Science Research Network]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Karlan, Pamela S.}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Bisexual women]]\n[[Category:Bisexual writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American attorneys]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from the United States]]\n[[Category:Law clerks of the Supreme Court of the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Stanford Law School faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia School of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:Women legal scholars]]\n[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Bisexual academics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American legal scholar}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Pamela Karlan\n| birth_name = Pamela Susan Karlan\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1959|1|1}}\n| birth_place = \n| nationality = [[Americans|American]]\n| education = [[Yale University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| occupation = American legal scholar\n| years_active = 1984\u2013present\n| partner = [[Viola Canales]]\n}}\n'''Pamela Susan Karlan''' (born February 1, 1959) is an American professor of law at [[Stanford Law School]]. A leading legal scholar on [[Voting rights in the United States|voting rights]] and political process, she served as U.S. Deputy Assistant Attorney General for Voting Rights in the [[United States Department of Justice Civil Division]] from 2014 to 2015.<ref>{{ cite news | last = Taylor | first = Stuart | title = An excellent Supreme Court shortlist | work = National Journal | publisher = [[Atlantic Media|Atlantic Media Company]] | url = http://www.nationaljournal.com/njmagazine/or_20100410_3801.php | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100412025442/http://www.nationaljournal.com/njmagazine/or_20100410_3801.php | archivedate = 2010-04-12 }}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nKarlan earned her B.A. degree in history from [[Yale University]] in 1980, as well as an M.A. degree in history and [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree in 1984.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web | title = Profile: Pamela S. Karlan | url = http://www.law.stanford.edu/directory/profile/32/ | publisher = Stanford Law School | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080605222907/http://www.law.stanford.edu/directory/profile/32/ | archivedate = 2008-06-05 }}</ref> At [[Yale Law School]], she served as an article and book reviews editor of the ''[[Yale Law Journal]]''.<ref name=\"cv\">{{cite web | last = Karlan | first = Pamela S. | title = CV | url = https://www-cdn.law.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/2015.KarlanCV.December1.pdf |accessdate = 22 January 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAfter graduation from law school, Karlan worked as a [[law clerk]] for former U.S. District Judge [[Abraham David Sofaer]] of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York|Southern District of New York]] from 1984 to 1985. She went on to clerk for [[U.S. Supreme Court Justice]] [[Harry Blackmun]] the following year. In a 1995 oral history with [[Harold Koh]], Blackmun revealed that his dissent in ''[[Bowers v. Hardwick]]'' had been written primarily by Karlan. He said that Karlan \"did a lot of very effective writing, and I owe a lot to her and her ability in getting that dissent out. She felt very strongly about it, and I think is correct in her approach to it. I think the dissent is correct.\"<ref>{{cite news | last = Volokh | first = Eugene | title = Saturday, April 23, 2005 | publisher = The Volokh Conspiracy: The Washington Post | date = 23 April 2005 | accessdate = 23 March 2015 | url = http://volokh.com/archives/archive_2005_04_17-2005_04_23.shtml#1114025448 }}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter her clerkships, Karlan worked as an assistant counsel at the [[NAACP]] [[NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund|Legal Defense and Educational Fund]] from 1986 to 1988.\n\nFrom 1988 to 1998, Karlan taught law at the [[University of Virginia]] [[University of Virginia School of Law|School of Law]], where she won the All-University Outstanding Teaching Award in 1995\u201396 and the [[State Council of Higher Education for Virginia]]'s Outstanding Faculty Award in 1997.<ref name=\"bio\" /> In 1998, Karlan joined the faculty of [[Stanford Law School]]. She is the school's Kenneth and Harle Montgomery Professor of [[Public interest law|Public Interest Law]]. In 2004, Karlan cofounded the Stanford Supreme Court Litigation [[Legal clinic|Clinic]], through which students litigate live cases before the [[U.S. Supreme Court]].<ref name=\"cv\" /> In 2002, Karlan won the school's prestigious John Bingham Hurlbut Award for Excellence in Teaching.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nKarlan has frequently commented on legal matters for ''[[PBS NewsHour]]''. During the disputed [[2000 United States presidential election|2000 presidential election]], she appeared regularly in the news media to discuss its comportment with constitutional law. In the aftermath of the election, Karlan, [[Samuel Issacharoff]], and [[Richard Pildes]] adapted two chapters from the law school casebook that they co-authored into a book entitled, ''When Elections Go Bad: The Law of Democracy and the Presidential Election of 2000''.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n\nOn December 4, 2019, Karlan\u2014alongside law professors [[Noah Feldman]], [[Michael Gerhardt]], and [[Jonathan Turley]]\u2014testified before the House Judiciary Committee regarding the constitutional grounds for presidential impeachment in the [[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump|Impeachment inquiry of President Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"2019 - New York Times - Who Is\">{{cite news |last1=Fadulu |first1=Lola |title=Who Is Pamela Karlan? Legal Leader Committed to Progressive Causes |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/04/us/politics/pamela-karlan.html |work=The New York Times |date=4 December 2019}}</ref> She made a controversial statement delivered during the December 2019, impeachment hearing of President Trump, \u201cContrary to what President Trump has said, Article 2 [of the Constitution] does not give him the power to do anything he wants,\u201d testified Pamela Karlan, a professor at Stanford Law School. \u201cThe Constitution says there can be no titles of nobility, so while the president can name his son Barron, he can\u2019t make him a baron.\u201d Karlan apologized afterward. <ref>C-Span: Professor Pamela Karlan references Barron Trump and later apologizes for it. Dec 4, 2019. </ref>  \n\nKarlan is a member of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]], the [[American Academy of Appellate Lawyers]], and the [[American Law Institute]].<ref name=\"bio\"/>\n\n=== Public service ===\nIn 2003, she was appointed to the [[California Fair Political Practices Commission]] by [[California State Controller|Controller]] [[Steve Westly]]. Until 2005, she served as commissioner to help implement and enforce [[California]]\u2019s [[Campaign finance in the United States|campaign finance]], [[Lobbying in the United States|lobbying]], and [[conflict of interest]] laws.<ref name=\"cv\" />\n\nOn December 20, 2013, Karlan was appointed by the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] to serve as the U.S. Deputy Assistant Attorney General for [[Voting rights in the United States|Voting Rights]] in the [[United States Department of Justice Civil Rights Division]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Gerstein | first = Josh | title = Karlan to take Justice Department voting rights post | url = http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2013/12/karlan-to-take-justice-department-voting-rights-post-180045.html?hp=l10 | date = 20 December 2013 | accessdate = 23 March 2015 | work = [[Politico|The Politico]] | publisher = Capitol News Company }}</ref> The position did not require confirmation by the [[U.S. Senate]]. Karlan took up her post on January 13, 2014, and served for one year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/person/?pamelakarlan|title=Pamela S. Karlan {{!}} C-SPAN.org|website=www.c-span.org|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Gregg | first = Remington | title = HRC Blog: Pamela Karlan takes helm as Deputy Assistant Attorney General in DOJ Civil Rights Division | website = hrc.org | publisher = Human Rights Campaign | url = http://www.hrc.org/blog/entry/pamela-karlan-take-helm-as-deputy-assistant-attorney-general-in-doj-civil-r | date = 13 January 2014 | accessdate = 23 March 2014 }}</ref> For her work in implementing the Supreme Court decision in ''[[United States v. Windsor]]'', she received the Attorney General\u2019s Award for Exceptional Service, the DOJ's highest award for employee performance.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|title=Pamela S. Karlan Biography|url=https://law.stanford.edu/directory/pamela-s-karlan/|website=Stanford Law School|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThroughout her career, Karlan has been an advocate before the [[U.S. Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite news |first= Adam |last= Liptak | title = So, guy walks up to the bar, and Scalia says... | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2005/12/31/politics/31mirth.html | work = [[The New York Times]] | date = 31 December 2005 }}</ref> She was mentioned as [[Barack Obama Supreme Court candidates|a potential candidate]] to replace Supreme Court Justice [[David Souter]] when he retired in 2009.<ref>{{cite news | title = Articles about Pamela S. Karlan | work = [[The New York Times]] | url = http://topics.nytimes.com/topics/reference/timestopics/people/k/pamela_s_karlan/index.html  }}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nPeter Baker, a New York Times political writer, described the subject as \"a full-throated, unapologetic liberal torchbearer\".<ref>Baker, Peter. (25 May 2009). \"Favorites of Left Don\u2019t Make Obama\u2019s Court List\". [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/26/us/politics/26court.html New York Times website] Retrieved 1 February 2020.</ref>  Karlan has said that the United States should help Ukraine fight Russia so that the United States does not have to fight Russia on its own territory.<ref>{{cite news |first= Tim |last= Hains | title = Professor Karlan: Ukraine Is Important \"So We Can Fight The Russians There And We Don't Have To Fight Them Here\" | url = https://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2019/12/04/professor_karlan_ukraine_is_important_so_we_can_fight_the_russians_there_and_we_dont_have_to_fight_them_here.html | work = [[RealClearPolitics]] | date = 4 December 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKarlan told ''[[The Politico|Politico]]'' in 2009, \"It's no secret at all that I'm counted among the [[LGBT]] crowd\".<ref name=polico_20090505>{{cite news |first=Josh |last=Gerstein | work = [[The Politico]] |url= http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0509/22106.html |title=Groups push for first gay Supreme Court justice |date=5 May 2009 |accessdate=12 April 2010 | publisher = Capitol News Company}}</ref> She has described herself as an example of \"snarky, [[bisexual]], Jewish women\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acslaw.org/expertforum/stanford-law-professor-pam-karlan-concludes-2006-acs-national-convention/|title=American Constitution Society Blog: Stanford Law Professor Pam Karlan concludes 2006 ACS National Convention|last=|first=|date=22 June 2006|website=|publisher=American Constitution Society for Law and Policy|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref> Her partner is writer [[Viola Canales]].<ref>{{cite news  |first= Esselink |last= Jean Ann | title = On our radar \u2013 An overdue thank you To Pamela Karlan | work = The New Civil Rights Movement | url = http://www.thenewcivilrightsmovement.com/on-our-radar-an-overdue-thank-you-to-pamela-karlan/news/2013/12/29/80872 | date = 29 December 2013 | accessdate =23 March 2015  }}</ref>\n\n==Works and publications==\n===Selected books===\n* {{cite book |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela S. |title=A Constitution for All Times |date=2013 |publisher=MIT Press |location=Cambridge, MA |isbn=978-0-262-01989-7 |oclc=863038741|jstor=j.ctt9qf8bs }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Issacharoff |first1=Samuel |last2=Karlan |first2=Pamela S. |last3=Pildes |first3=Richard H. |last4=Persily |first4=Nathan |title=The Law of Democracy: Legal Structure of the Political Process |date=2016 |publisher=Foundation Pres |location=St. Paul, MN |isbn=9781628102253 |edition=5th |url=http://www.thelawofdemocracy.com/ |oclc=956640376}}\n\n===Selected journals===\n* {{cite journal |last1=Brennan |first1=William J. |last2=Ginsburg |first2=Ruth Bader |last3=Arnold |first3=Richard S. |last4=Griswold |first4=Erwin N. |last5=Karlan |first5=Pamela S. |last6=Koh |first6=Harold Hongju |title=A Tribute to Justice Harry A. Blackmun |journal=Harvard Law Review |date=1994 |volume=108 |issue=1 |pages=163\u20138 |issn=0017-811X |jstor=1341989|pmid=3333213 }}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela S. |title=The Supreme Court \u2013 Comments. Electing Judges, Judging Elections, and the Lessons of Caperton |journal=Harvard Law Review |date=November 2009 |volume=123 |issue=1 |pages=80\u2013103 |url=https://harvardlawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/karlan09.pdf |issn=0017-811X |oclc=472051099}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela |title=Henry J. Miller Lecture Series: Old Reasons, New Reasons, No Reasons |journal=Georgia State University Law Review |date=Summer 2011 |volume=27 |issue=4 |url= https://readingroom.law.gsu.edu/gsulr/vol27/iss4/2/ |issn=8755-6847 |oclc=8092032473}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela S. |title=In Memoriam: William J. Stuntz |journal=Harvard Law Review |date=June 2011 |volume=124 |issue=8 |pages=1841\u20131843 |url=https://harvardlawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/vol124_stuntz_tribute.pdf}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Karlan |first1=Pamela |title=The Swing Justice: Reflections on the Career of Justice Anthony Kennedy. Panel 1: Abortion and Gay Rights |journal=Georgia State University Law Review |date=Spring 2019 |volume=35 |issue=5 (Supplement) |pages=871\u2013905 |url= https://readingroom.law.gsu.edu/gsulr/vol35/iss5/1/ |issn=8755-6847 |oclc=1101178994}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://law.stanford.edu/directory/pamela-s-karlan/ Pamela S. Karlan] at [[Stanford University Law School]]\n* {{C-SPAN|Pamela Karlan}}\n* [https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/cf_dev/AbsByAuth.cfm?per_id=136810 Pamela S. Karlan] at [[Social Science Research Network]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Karlan, Pamela S.}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Bisexual women]]\n[[Category:Bisexual writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American attorneys]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from the United States]]\n[[Category:Law clerks of the Supreme Court of the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Stanford Law School faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia School of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:Women legal scholars]]\n[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Bisexual academics]]\n", "name_user": "Poldavia", "label": "safe", "comment": "+ image", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pamela_S._Karlan"}
{"title_page": "Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel", "text_new": "[[File:PfeffelGC.jpg|thumb|Gottlieb Conrad Pfeffel, painting by Georg Friedrich Adolph Schoner, 1809]]\n[[File:Pfeffel diktiert seiner Tochter.jpg|thumb|right|250px|''Pfeffel dictating to his daughter'', image accompanying a text dedicated to [[Johann Georg Jacobi]], 1800]]\n'''Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel''' (28 June 1736 \u2013 1 May 1809) was a French-German writer and translator from the [[Pfeffel family]]. His texts were put to music by [[Ludwig van Beethoven]], [[Joseph Haydn]] and [[Franz Schubert]]. He is sometimes also known as '''Am\u00e9d\u00e9e''' or '''Th\u00e9ophile''' Conrad Pfeffel, which is the French translation of Gottlieb (\"Godlove\").\n\n==Biography==\nGottlieb Konrad Pfeffel was born in [[Colmar]].  His father, Johann Konrad Pfeffel, was the mayor of Colmar and a legal consultant of the French king, but died when Gottlieb was only two years old.  He was raised by his brother [[Christian Friedrich Pfeffel]], who was ten years older. He went in 1751 to the [[University of Halle-Wittenberg|University of Halle]] to study Law, with the intention of becoming a diplomat. There, he was a student of the philosopher [[Christian Wolff (philosopher)|Christian Wolff]]. In 1752, he translated [[Johann Joachim Spalding]]'s ''Gedanken \u00fcber den Werth der Gef\u00fchle in dem Christenthum'' in French. In 1754, he went to Dresden for treatment of an eye problem; there, he met the poet [[Christian F\u00fcrchtegott Gellert]]. His eye condition deteriorated, and in 1758, after an operation, he became completely blind and had to abandon his studies.<ref name=Spiegel>{{cite web|title=Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel|url= http://gutenberg.spiegel.de/autor/460| publisher = Der Spiegel|accessdate=8 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=Bautz>{{cite web|title=Biographisch-Bibliographisches Kirchenlexikon|publisher=Traugott Bautz| language = German|year=2007}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1759, he married Margaretha Cleophe Divoux, a merchant's daughter from [[Strasbourg]]. They had thirteen children together, of whom 7 died before adulthood. He started to establish himself as a writer and translator.  In 1762, he translated [[Magnus Gottfried Lichtwer]]'s ''Fabeln'' in French.  He also worked on a translation into German of [[Claude Fleury]]'s ''Histoire eccl\u00e9siastique''. He opened a military academy for aristocratic Protestants in 1773, since these boys were not allowed at the military academy of Paris.  He joined the [[Helvetic Society]] in 1776, and in 1782 became a citizen of the city of [[Biel]] (Bienne) in Switzerland, and became an honorary member of the city council in 1783. The [[Prussian Academy of Arts]] made him an honorary member in 1788.<ref name=Spiegel/><ref name=Bautz/>\n\nAfter the French Revolution, he lost the military academy and his fortune, and found jobs with the educational board of Colmar, with the publisher T\u00fcbingen-[[Johann Friedrich Cotta|Cotta]], and as a translator, until [[Napoleon I]] granted him an annual pension in 1806. He wrote many articles for the magazine ''Flora''. In 1808 he became an honorary member of the [[Bavarian Academy of Sciences and Humanities]]. He died the next year.<ref name=Spiegel/><ref name=Bautz/>\n\nHis poem ''Der freie Mann'' was put to music by Ludwig van Beethoven (catalogue number [[WoO (Beethoven)|WoO]] 117) in 1794 or 1795.<ref>{{cite web|last=van Beethoven |first=Ludwig |title=Vocal Music (Stolte, Schreier, Olbertz) |url=http://www.naxosmusiclibrary.com/preview/catalogueinfo.asp?catID=0020842BC&path=1 |publisher=Naxos |accessdate=8 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008064401/http://www.naxosmusiclibrary.com/preview/catalogueinfo.asp?catID=0020842BC&path=1 |archivedate=8 October 2011 }}</ref> Franz Schubert made a [[lied]] of his text ''Der Vaterm\u00f6rder'' ([[Otto Erich Deutsch|D]]10),<ref>{{cite web|last=Schubert |first=Friedrich |title=Lied - Settings of Various Poets |edition=29 |url=http://www.naxosmusiclibrary.com/preview/catalogueinfo.asp?catID=8.570838&path=1 |publisher=Naxos |accessdate=8 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008064606/http://www.naxosmusiclibrary.com/preview/catalogueinfo.asp?catID=8.570838&path=1 |archivedate=8 October 2011 }}</ref> and [[Leopold Kozeluch]] put music to his [[cantata]] for the blind Austrian singer [[Maria Theresia von Paradis]].<ref>{{cite journal| title= An account of Mademoiselle Theresa Paradis| journal= [[The London Magazine]] | year= 1785| volume= 4}}</ref> In 1773, his ''Philemon und Baucis: Ein Schauspiel in Versen von einem Aufzuge'', a play in verse in one act, was turned into a [[Singspiel]] for a [[marionette]] theater by [[Joseph Haydn]] with the new title ''Philemon und Baucis oder Jupiters Reise auf die Erde'' (''Philemon and Baucis or Jupiter's Travels to the Earth'').  It was changed into a regular opera in 1776.<ref>{{cite web | title = Philemon und Baucis |url=http://www.classicalarchives.com/work/465715.html#tvf=tracks&tv=about |publisher=Classicalarchives.com |accessdate=8 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nPfeffel was a friend or acquaintance of many well-known persons of his period, including [[Voltaire]], [[Vittorio Alfieri]] and the Swiss poet [[Johann Kaspar Lavater]], which whom he corresponded for many years. In 1839, his niece [[:ru:\u041f\u0444\u0435\u0444\u0444\u0435\u043b\u044c, \u042d\u0440\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430|Ernestine von Pfeffel]] (1810-94) married [[Fyodor Tyutchev]], one of the most famous Russian poets.\n\nA statue of Pfeffel by [[Andr\u00e9 Friedrich]] was placed in the [[Unterlinden Museum]] in 1859, and a copy of that statue was placed on the Grand Rue in Colmar in 1927.<ref>{{cite web|title=Monument dedicated to Pfeffel|url=http://www.ot-colmar.fr/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=16809&Itemid=215&lang=en|publisher=Office de Tourisme de Colmar|accessdate=8 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n[[File:Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Portrait from Volume 10 of the 1841 edition of the ''Poetische Versuche'']]\n*''Der Einsiedler'', 1761\n*''Philemon und Baucis: Ein Schauspiel in Versen von einem Aufzuge'': 6 editions published between 1763 and 1773 in 4 languages: reprinted as ''Philemon und Baucis, oder, Jupiters Reise auf die Erde : deutsche Marionetten-Oper'': music by [[Joseph Haydn]], 1773\n*''Dramatische Kinderspiele'': 5 volumes published between 1763 and 1774: translated in French\n*''Magazin f\u00fcr den Verstand und das Herz'', 1764, translated in Russian and French\n*''Neue Beytr\u00e4ge zur Deutschen Maculatur'': 2 editions published in 1766\n*''Freymund, oder der \u00fcbel angebrachte Stolz: ein Lustspiel in f\u00fcnf Aufz\u00fcgen'', 1770\n*''Der Einsiedler: ein Trauerspiel in Versen von einem Aufzuge'', 1771\n*''Serena: ein b\u00fcrgerliches Trauerspiel'', 1776, with [[Paul Landois]]\n*''Lieder f\u00fcr die Colmarische Kriegsschule'', 1778\n*''Fabeln, der Helvetischen Gesellschaft gewidmet'': 8 editions published between 1783 and 1815\n*''Histoire du regne de Marie-Th\u00e9r\u00e8se'', 1786\n*''Poetische Versuche von Gottlieb Conrad Pfeffel'': 71 editions published between 1789 and 1968 in 4 language: also published in 3 parts, with a further 11 editions, and with three additional parts in 1802, eventually growing to ten bands by 1810\n*''Prosaische Versuche'': 27 editions published between 1794 and 1813, expanded to 10 bands by 1810\n*''Contes et nouvelles'', 1822 (French translation of a selection of his work)\n*''Briefe \u00fcber Religion an Bettina'': 7 editions published in 1824 in 3 language\n*''Ausgew\u00e4hlte Unterhaltungen'', Volumes 5-6, 1828\n*''Bloemlezing uit de fabelen en vertellingen'', Dutch translation from 1832\n*''Fabeln und poetische Erz\u00e4hlungen'': 9 editions published between 1840 and 1861: translated as ''Fables et po\u00e9sies choisies'' in 1840\n*''Historisches Magazin f\u00fcr Verstand und Herz'', 1840\n*''Poetische Werke: Mit Biographie und Portrait: Volumes 1-3'', 1841\n*''G C Pfeffel's Epistel an die Nachwelt'', 1859\n*''Pfeffel-Album: Gaben els\u00e4ssischer Dichter'', 1859\n*''Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffels Fremdenbuch mit biographischen und culturgeschichtlichen Erl\u00e4uterungen'', 1892\n*''Skorpion und Hirtenknabe; Fabeln, Epigramme, poetische Erz\u00e4hlungen, Biographie eines Pudels und andere Prosa'', 1970\n*''Biographie eines Pudels und andere Satiren'': 2 editions published in 1987\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Th\u00e9ophile-Conrad Pfeffel de Colmar; souvenirs biographiques'', by Lina Bernard, Delafontaine & Rouge, 1866\n*''Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel's theatralische Belustigungen. Ein Beitrag zur geschichte des franz\u00f6sischen Dramas in Deutschland'', by Karl Worzel, E. Schmidt, 1911\n*''Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel. Ein Beitrag zur Kulturgeschichte des Elsass'', by Edgar Guhde, Keller, 1964\n*''Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel : Satiriker und Philanthrop, 1736-1809'': Catalogue of the exhibition at the [[Badische Landesbibliothek]] in [[Karlsruhe]] in 1986\n*''Pfeffel, l'Europ\u00e9en: esprit fran\u00e7ais et culture allemande en Alsace au XVIIIe si\u00e8cle'', by Gabriel Braeuner, Nu\u00e9e Bleue, 1994\n*''Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel (1736-1809) : Signaturen der Sp\u00e4taufkl\u00e4rung am Oberrhein'', by Achim Aurnhammer and Wilhelm K\u00fchlmann, Rombach, 2010\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pfeffel, Gottlib Konrad}}\n[[Category:1736 births]]\n[[Category:1809 deaths]]\n[[Category:French writers in German]]\n[[Category:French opera librettists]]\n[[Category:Blind people from Germany]]\n[[Category:Blind writers]]\n[[Category:People from Colmar]]\n[[Category:Alsatian-German people]]\n[[Category:French male dramatists and playwrights]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:PfeffelGC.jpg|thumb|Gottlieb Conrad Pfeffel, painting by Georg Friedrich Adolph Schoner, 1809]]\n[[File:Pfeffel diktiert seiner Tochter.jpg|thumb|right|250px|''Pfeffel dictating to his daughter'', image accompanying a text dedicated to [[Johann Georg Jacobi]], 1800]]\n'''Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel''' (28 June 1736 \u2013 1 May 1809) was a French-German writer and translator, whose texts were put to music by [[Ludwig van Beethoven]], [[Joseph Haydn]] and [[Franz Schubert]]. He is sometimes also known as '''Am\u00e9d\u00e9e''' or '''Th\u00e9ophile''' Conrad Pfeffel, which is the French translation of Gottlieb (\"Godlove\").\n\n==Biography==\nGottlieb Konrad Pfeffel was born in [[Colmar]].  His father, Johann Konrad Pfeffel, was the mayor of Colmar and a legal consultant of the French king, but died when Gottlieb was only two years old.  He was raised by his brother [[Christian Friedrich Pfeffel]], who was ten years older. He went in 1751 to the [[University of Halle-Wittenberg|University of Halle]] to study Law, with the intention of becoming a diplomat. There, he was a student of the philosopher [[Christian Wolff (philosopher)|Christian Wolff]]. In 1752, he translated [[Johann Joachim Spalding]]'s ''Gedanken \u00fcber den Werth der Gef\u00fchle in dem Christenthum'' in French. In 1754, he went to Dresden for treatment of an eye problem; there, he met the poet [[Christian F\u00fcrchtegott Gellert]]. His eye condition deteriorated, and in 1758, after an operation, he became completely blind and had to abandon his studies.<ref name=Spiegel>{{cite web|title=Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel|url= http://gutenberg.spiegel.de/autor/460| publisher = Der Spiegel|accessdate=8 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=Bautz>{{cite web|title=Biographisch-Bibliographisches Kirchenlexikon|publisher=Traugott Bautz| language = German|year=2007}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1759, he married Margaretha Cleophe Divoux, a merchant's daughter from [[Strasbourg]]. They had thirteen children together, of whom 7 died before adulthood. He started to establish himself as a writer and translator.  In 1762, he translated [[Magnus Gottfried Lichtwer]]'s ''Fabeln'' in French.  He also worked on a translation into German of [[Claude Fleury]]'s ''Histoire eccl\u00e9siastique''. He opened a military academy for aristocratic Protestants in 1773, since these boys were not allowed at the military academy of Paris.  He joined the [[Helvetic Society]] in 1776, and in 1782 became a citizen of the city of [[Biel]] (Bienne) in Switzerland, and became an honorary member of the city council in 1783. The [[Prussian Academy of Arts]] made him an honorary member in 1788.<ref name=Spiegel/><ref name=Bautz/>\n\nAfter the French Revolution, he lost the military academy and his fortune, and found jobs with the educational board of Colmar, with the publisher T\u00fcbingen-[[Johann Friedrich Cotta|Cotta]], and as a translator, until [[Napoleon I]] granted him an annual pension in 1806. He wrote many articles for the magazine ''Flora''. In 1808 he became an honorary member of the [[Bavarian Academy of Sciences and Humanities]]. He died the next year.<ref name=Spiegel/><ref name=Bautz/>\n\nHis poem ''Der freie Mann'' was put to music by Ludwig van Beethoven (catalogue number [[WoO (Beethoven)|WoO]] 117) in 1794 or 1795.<ref>{{cite web|last=van Beethoven |first=Ludwig |title=Vocal Music (Stolte, Schreier, Olbertz) |url=http://www.naxosmusiclibrary.com/preview/catalogueinfo.asp?catID=0020842BC&path=1 |publisher=Naxos |accessdate=8 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008064401/http://www.naxosmusiclibrary.com/preview/catalogueinfo.asp?catID=0020842BC&path=1 |archivedate=8 October 2011 }}</ref> Franz Schubert made a [[lied]] of his text ''Der Vaterm\u00f6rder'' ([[Otto Erich Deutsch|D]]10),<ref>{{cite web|last=Schubert |first=Friedrich |title=Lied - Settings of Various Poets |edition=29 |url=http://www.naxosmusiclibrary.com/preview/catalogueinfo.asp?catID=8.570838&path=1 |publisher=Naxos |accessdate=8 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008064606/http://www.naxosmusiclibrary.com/preview/catalogueinfo.asp?catID=8.570838&path=1 |archivedate=8 October 2011 }}</ref> and [[Leopold Kozeluch]] put music to his [[cantata]] for the blind Austrian singer [[Maria Theresia von Paradis]].<ref>{{cite journal| title= An account of Mademoiselle Theresa Paradis| journal= [[The London Magazine]] | year= 1785| volume= 4}}</ref> In 1773, his ''Philemon und Baucis: Ein Schauspiel in Versen von einem Aufzuge'', a play in verse in one act, was turned into a [[Singspiel]] for a [[marionette]] theater by [[Joseph Haydn]] with the new title ''Philemon und Baucis oder Jupiters Reise auf die Erde'' (''Philemon and Baucis or Jupiter's Travels to the Earth'').  It was changed into a regular opera in 1776.<ref>{{cite web | title = Philemon und Baucis |url=http://www.classicalarchives.com/work/465715.html#tvf=tracks&tv=about |publisher=Classicalarchives.com |accessdate=8 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nPfeffel was a friend or acquaintance of many well-known persons of his period, including [[Voltaire]], [[Vittorio Alfieri]] and the Swiss poet [[Johann Kaspar Lavater]], which whom he corresponded for many years. In 1839, his niece [[:ru:\u041f\u0444\u0435\u0444\u0444\u0435\u043b\u044c, \u042d\u0440\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430|Ernestine von Pfeffel]] (1810-94) married [[Fyodor Tyutchev]], one of the most famous Russian poets.\n\nA statue of Pfeffel by [[Andr\u00e9 Friedrich]] was placed in the [[Unterlinden Museum]] in 1859, and a copy of that statue was placed on the Grand Rue in Colmar in 1927.<ref>{{cite web|title=Monument dedicated to Pfeffel|url=http://www.ot-colmar.fr/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=16809&Itemid=215&lang=en|publisher=Office de Tourisme de Colmar|accessdate=8 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n[[File:Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Portrait from Volume 10 of the 1841 edition of the ''Poetische Versuche'']]\n*''Der Einsiedler'', 1761\n*''Philemon und Baucis: Ein Schauspiel in Versen von einem Aufzuge'': 6 editions published between 1763 and 1773 in 4 languages: reprinted as ''Philemon und Baucis, oder, Jupiters Reise auf die Erde : deutsche Marionetten-Oper'': music by [[Joseph Haydn]], 1773\n*''Dramatische Kinderspiele'': 5 volumes published between 1763 and 1774: translated in French\n*''Magazin f\u00fcr den Verstand und das Herz'', 1764, translated in Russian and French\n*''Neue Beytr\u00e4ge zur Deutschen Maculatur'': 2 editions published in 1766\n*''Freymund, oder der \u00fcbel angebrachte Stolz: ein Lustspiel in f\u00fcnf Aufz\u00fcgen'', 1770\n*''Der Einsiedler: ein Trauerspiel in Versen von einem Aufzuge'', 1771\n*''Serena: ein b\u00fcrgerliches Trauerspiel'', 1776, with [[Paul Landois]]\n*''Lieder f\u00fcr die Colmarische Kriegsschule'', 1778\n*''Fabeln, der Helvetischen Gesellschaft gewidmet'': 8 editions published between 1783 and 1815\n*''Histoire du regne de Marie-Th\u00e9r\u00e8se'', 1786\n*''Poetische Versuche von Gottlieb Conrad Pfeffel'': 71 editions published between 1789 and 1968 in 4 language: also published in 3 parts, with a further 11 editions, and with three additional parts in 1802, eventually growing to ten bands by 1810\n*''Prosaische Versuche'': 27 editions published between 1794 and 1813, expanded to 10 bands by 1810\n*''Contes et nouvelles'', 1822 (French translation of a selection of his work)\n*''Briefe \u00fcber Religion an Bettina'': 7 editions published in 1824 in 3 language\n*''Ausgew\u00e4hlte Unterhaltungen'', Volumes 5-6, 1828\n*''Bloemlezing uit de fabelen en vertellingen'', Dutch translation from 1832\n*''Fabeln und poetische Erz\u00e4hlungen'': 9 editions published between 1840 and 1861: translated as ''Fables et po\u00e9sies choisies'' in 1840\n*''Historisches Magazin f\u00fcr Verstand und Herz'', 1840\n*''Poetische Werke: Mit Biographie und Portrait: Volumes 1-3'', 1841\n*''G C Pfeffel's Epistel an die Nachwelt'', 1859\n*''Pfeffel-Album: Gaben els\u00e4ssischer Dichter'', 1859\n*''Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffels Fremdenbuch mit biographischen und culturgeschichtlichen Erl\u00e4uterungen'', 1892\n*''Skorpion und Hirtenknabe; Fabeln, Epigramme, poetische Erz\u00e4hlungen, Biographie eines Pudels und andere Prosa'', 1970\n*''Biographie eines Pudels und andere Satiren'': 2 editions published in 1987\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Th\u00e9ophile-Conrad Pfeffel de Colmar; souvenirs biographiques'', by Lina Bernard, Delafontaine & Rouge, 1866\n*''Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel's theatralische Belustigungen. Ein Beitrag zur geschichte des franz\u00f6sischen Dramas in Deutschland'', by Karl Worzel, E. Schmidt, 1911\n*''Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel. Ein Beitrag zur Kulturgeschichte des Elsass'', by Edgar Guhde, Keller, 1964\n*''Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel : Satiriker und Philanthrop, 1736-1809'': Catalogue of the exhibition at the [[Badische Landesbibliothek]] in [[Karlsruhe]] in 1986\n*''Pfeffel, l'Europ\u00e9en: esprit fran\u00e7ais et culture allemande en Alsace au XVIIIe si\u00e8cle'', by Gabriel Braeuner, Nu\u00e9e Bleue, 1994\n*''Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel (1736-1809) : Signaturen der Sp\u00e4taufkl\u00e4rung am Oberrhein'', by Achim Aurnhammer and Wilhelm K\u00fchlmann, Rombach, 2010\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Gottlieb Konrad Pfeffel}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pfeffel, Gottlib Konrad}}\n[[Category:1736 births]]\n[[Category:1809 deaths]]\n[[Category:French writers in German]]\n[[Category:French opera librettists]]\n[[Category:Blind people from Germany]]\n[[Category:Blind writers]]\n[[Category:People from Colmar]]\n[[Category:Alsatian-German people]]\n[[Category:French male dramatists and playwrights]]\n", "name_user": "Ghirlandajo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Pfeffel family", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottlieb_Konrad_Pfeffel"}
{"title_page": "Hunza Valley", "text_new": "{{For|the article about the former princely state|Hunza (princely state)}}\n{{original research|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox valley\n| name               = Hunza Valley\n| other_name         = \n| native_name        = \u06c1\u0646\u0632\u0648\n| native_name_lang   = bsk\n| translation        = \n| photo              = File:Rakaposhi, Nagar GB (Pakistan).jpg\n| photo_caption      = The {{Convert|7788|m}} tall [[Rakaposhi]] mountain towers over Hunza\n<!--    MAP     -->\n| map                = Gilgit Baltistan#Pakistan\n| map_image          = \n| map_caption        = \n<!--  Location  -->\n| location           = \n| country            = {{flagicon|Pakistan}} [[Pakistan]]\n| region             = {{flagicon|Gilgit-Baltistan}} [[Gilgit-Baltistan]]\n| state              = \n| district           = [[Hunza District]]\n| city               = \n| relief             = \n| label              = \n| label_position     = \n| coordinates        = {{coord|36.316942|N|74.649900|E|display=inline}} \n| coordinates_ref    = <ref>{{cite web |title=Hunza on Google Maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Hunza+Valley/ |website=Google Maps |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n<!-- Statistics -->  \n| elevation          = \n| elevation_m        = \n| elevation_ft       = \n| elevation_ref      = \n| length             = \n| length_mi          = \n| length_km          = \n| length_orientation = \n| length_note        = \n| width              = \n| width_mi           = \n| width_km           = \n| width_orientation  = \n| width_note         = \n| area               = \n| area_mi2           = \n| area_km2           = \n| depth              = \n| depth_ft           = \n| depth_m            = \n| type               = \n| age                = \n| border             = \n| topo               = \n| traversed          = \n| river              = \n<!-- Below --> \n| footnotes          = \n| embed              = \n}}\n'''Hunza''' ({{lang-bsk|\u06c1\u0646\u0632\u0648}}, [[Wakhi language|Wakhi]]: \"{{lang|wbl|shina}}\", {{lang-ur|{{nq|\u06c1\u0646\u0632\u06c1}}}}) is a mountainous valley in the [[Gilgit-Baltistan|Gilgit-Baltistan region]] of [[Pakistan]]. Hunza is situated in the extreme northern part of Pakistan, bordering with the [[Wakhan Corridor]] of [[Afghanistan]] and the [[Xinjiang|Xinjiang region]] of [[China]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mountainous Valley situated in extreme northern part of Pakistan |url=https://www.dreamstime.com/hunza-mountainous-valley-gilgit-baltistan-region-pakistan-hunza-situated-extreme-northern-part-image107691385 |website=www.dreamstime.com |accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Hunza valley is situated at an elevation of 2,438 meters (7,999 feet).  Geographicaly, Hunza consists of three regions, Upper Hunza ([[Gojal]]), Central Hunza (\"Hunza Valley\") and Lower Hunza (\"Shinaki\"). \n\n== History ==\n{{main|State of Hunza}}\n[[File: Baltit Fort, Karimabad, Hunza, Gilgit Baltistan.jpg|thumb|[[Baltit Fort]], the former residence of the Mirs of Hunza]]\nHunza was formerly a [[princely state]] bordering  [[Xinjiang]] (autonomous region of China) to the northeast and [[Pamir Mountains|Pamir]] to the northwest, which survived until 1974, when it was finally dissolved by [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]].  The state bordered the [[Gilgit Agency]] to the south and the former princely state of [[Nagar (princely state)|Nagar]] to the east. The state capital was the town of Baltit (also known as [[Karimabad (Hunza)|Karimabad]]); another old settlement is [[Ganish Village]] which means \"ancient gold\" village. Hunza was an independent principality for more than 900 years until the [[British Raj|British]] gained control of it and the neighboring valley of Nagar between 1889 and 1891 through military conquest. The then [[Tham (title)|Mir/Tham]] (ruler), branch of [[Katoor Dynasty|Katur Dynasty]], Safdar Khan of Hunza fled to [[Kashghar]] in China and sought what would now be called political asylum.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Valley|first1=Hunza|title=Hunza Valley|url=http://www.skardu.pk/hunza-valley/|website=www.skardu.pk|publisher=Skardu.pk|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Mir/Tham===\n{{main|Mir of Hunza}}\n\nAn account wrote by John Biddulph in his book ''[[Tribes of the Hindoo Koosh]]'' {{cquote|The ruling family of Hunza is called Ayesha (heavenly). The two states of [[Hunza (princely state)|Hunza]] and [[Nagar (princely state)|Nagar]] were formerly one, ruled by a branch of the Shahreis, the ruling family of [[Gilgit]], whose seat of government was Nager. First muslim came to Hunza-Nagar Valley some 1000 years (At the time of Imam Isl\u0101m Sh\u0101h 30th Imam Ismaili Muslims). After the introduction of [[Islam]] to Gilgit, married a daughter of Trakhan of [[Gilgit]], who bore him twin sons, named Moghlot and Girkis. From the former, the present ruling family of Nager is descended. The twins are said to have shown hostility to one another from birth. Thereupon their father, unable to settle the question of succession, divided his state between them, giving Girkis the north/west, and to Moghlot the south/east bank of the river.<ref>Tribes of the Hindoo Koosh by John Biddulph page 26</ref>}}\n\n===2010 Landslide===\nIn January 4, 2010, a landslide blocked the river and created [[Attabad Lake]] (also called shishket Lake), resulting in 20 deaths and 8 injuries and has effectively blocked about {{convert|26|km}} of the [[Karakoram Highway]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Waheed |first1=Abdul |title=The Attabad Landslide Disaster |url=https://pamirtimes.net/2013/01/04/the-attabad-landslide-disaster/ |accessdate=12 October 2019 |publisher=Pamir Times |date=4 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=SHISHKET LAKE CRISES \u2013 2010 \u2013 CHRONOLOGY OF EVENTS |url=http://www.ndma.gov.pk/new/aboutus/SHISHKET_lake_2010.pdf |website=ndma.gov.pk |publisher=[[National Disaster Management Authority (Pakistan)|NDMA]] |accessdate=12 October 2019 |date=27 July 2010}}</ref> The new lake extends {{convert|30|km|mi}} and rose to a depth of {{convert|400|ft|m}} when it was formed as the Hunza River backed up.<ref name=\"fourworlds_HiMaT_2013\">{{cite web | url=http://www.fourworlds.ca/documents/ASecondGreenRevolution.pdf | title=Needed: a second green revolution in Hunza | publisher=HiMaT | date=May 2013 | accessdate=26 November 2015 | pages=4 | author1=Michael Bopp | author2=Judie Bopp}} Karakorum Area Development Organization (KADO), Aliabad</ref> The landslide completely covered sections of the Karakoram Highway.<ref name=\"fourworlds_HiMaT_2013\" />\n\n===2018 Rescue mission===\n[[File:Hunza Tunnel.jpg|thumb|right|Tunnel]]\nOn 1 July 2018, [[Pakistan Army]] pilots in a daring mission rescued 3 foreign mountaineers stuck in snow avalanche at above the height of {{Convert|19000|ft}} on [[Ultar Sar|Ultar Sar Peak]] near Hunza. The perilous weather conditions had made it difficult for the Army helicopter to go forth with a rescue operation on the {{Convert|7,388|m}} high [[Ultar Sar]]. But they completed it. Bruce Normand and Timothy Miller from [[United Kingdom|UK]] successfully rescued alive while their companion Christian Huber from [[Austria]] had succumbed to avalanche.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pakistan Army Pilots rescued 3 foreign mountaineers |url=https://en.dailypakistan.com.pk/headline/pakistan-army-rescues-avalanche-stricken-british-mountaineers-in-hunza-valley/ |website=en.dailypakistan.com.pk |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mountainers News on Thenews.com.pk |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/336019-pakistan-army-rescues-two-british-mountaineers-stranded-on |website=www.thenews.com.pk |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nBritain's High Commissioner [[Thomas Drew (diplomat)|Thomas Drew]] in [[Pakistan]] termed the mission \u201cremarkable and dangerous\u201d and said:\n\n\u201c''Our gratitude to the [[Pakistan Army]] pilots who rescued two British climbers trapped by an avalanche on [[Ultar Sar|Ultar Sar Peak]] near Hunza. Our thoughts with their Austrian fellow climber who died\u201d''.\n<ref>{{cite web |title=Britain's High Commissioner in Pakistan admired Pak Army Pilots for rescued the two British Climbers |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/07/01/british-mountaineers-rescued-deadly-pakistan-avalanche-19000ft/ |website=www.telegraph.co.uk |accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Major General Asif Ghafoor also tweeted about it |url=https://www.forces.net/news/british-climbers-rescued-pakistan-army |website=www.forces.net |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== People ==\n{{main|Hunza people}}\nThe local languages spoken include [[Burushaski]], [[Wakhi language|Wakhi]] and [[Shina language|Shina]]. The literacy rate of the Hunza valley is more than 95%.<ref name=\"education dawn\">{{cite news|url=http://archives.dawn.com/archives/29975|title=Hunza disaster and schools|first=Shahid|last=Siddiqui|work=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> The historical area of Hunza and present northern Pakistan has had, over the centuries, mass migrations, conflicts and resettling of tribes and ethnicities, of which the [[Shina people|Dardic Shina]] race is the most prominent in regional history. People of the region have recounted their historical traditions down the generations. The Hunza Valley is also home to some [[Wakhi people|Wakhi]], who migrated there from northeastern Afghanistan beginning in the nineteenth century onwards.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Arts and Crafts of the Hunza Valley in Pakistan: Living Traditions in the Karakoram|last=Frembgen Wasim|first=Jurgen|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2017|isbn=978-0-19-940520-6|location=Karachi|pages=1}}</ref>\n\nThe longevity of Hunza people has been noted by some,<ref name=\"Wrench1938\">{{Cite book |year=1938 |author=Wrench, Dr Guy T |title=The Wheel of Health: A Study of the Hunza People and the Keys to Health |series=2009 reprint |place= |publisher=Review Press |isbn=978-0-9802976-6-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lMfSuHgabYoC&printsec=frontcover&dq=wheel+of+health#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=12 August 2010 }}</ref> but others refute this as a [[Longevity myths|longevity myth]] and cite a life expectancy of 110 years for men and 122 for women with a high standard deviation.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C02E2D9173CF93AA1575AC0A960958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2 | work=The New York Times | title=The Optimists Are Right | first=John | last=Tierney | date=29 September 1996}}</ref> There is no evidence that Hunza life expectancy is significantly above the average of poor, isolated regions of Pakistan. Claims of health and long life were almost always based solely on the statements by the local mir (king). An author who had significant and sustained contact with Burusho people, John Clark, reported that they were overall unhealthy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblelife.org/hunza.htm|title=Hunza \u2013 The Truth, Myths, and Lies About the Health and Diet of the \"Long-Lived\" People of Hunza, Pakistan, Hunza Bread and Pie Recipes.|website=www.biblelife.org}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[State of Hunza|State of Hunza (former)]]\n* [[Hunza\u2013Nagar District]]\n* [[Bagrot Valley]]\n* [[Naltar Valley]]\n* [[Shamanism in Hunza]]\n* [[Northern Areas|Northern Areas (former)]]\n* [[Silk Road transmission of Buddhism]]\n* [[Karakoram Highway]]\n* [[Karakoram Mountains]]\n* [[Neelam Valley]]\n* [[Kalasha Valley]]\n* [[Kaghan Valley]]\n* [[Nagar Valley]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Kreutzmann, Hermann, ''Karakoram in Transition: Culture, Development, and Ecology in the Hunza Valley'', Oxford University Press, 2006. {{ISBN|978-0-19-547210-3}}\n* Leitner, G. W. (1893): ''Dardistan in 1866, 1886 and 1893: Being An Account of the History, Religions, Customs, Legends, Fables and Songs of Gilgit, Chilas, Kandia (Gabrial) Yasin, Chitral, Hunza, Nagar and other parts of the Hindukush, as also a supplement to the second edition of The Hunza and Nagar Handbook. And An Epitome of Part III of the author\u2019s \u201cThe Languages and Races of Dardistan.\u201d'' First Reprint 1978. Manjusri Publishing House, New Delhi.\n* Lorimer, Lt. Col. D.L.R. ''Folk Tales of Hunza''. 1st edition 1935, Oslo. Three volumes. Vol. II, republished by the Institute of Folk Heritage, Islamabad. 1981.\n* Sidkey, M. H. \"Shamans and Mountain Spirits in Hunza.\" ''Asian Folklore Studies'', Vol. 53, No. 1 (1994), pp.&nbsp;67\u201396.\n* [https://hisamullah.wordpress.com/2012/04/29/tarikh-e-ehd-e-ateeq-e-riasat-e-hunza-english-translation/ History of Ancient Era Hunza State] By Haji Qudratullah Beg English Translation By Lt Col (Rtd) Saadullah Beg, TI(M)\n* {{citation |year=1938 |author=Wrench, Dr Guy T |title=The Wheel of Health: A Study of the Hunza People and the Keys to Health |series=2009 reprint |place= |publisher=Review Press |isbn=978-0-9802976-6-9 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=lMfSuHgabYoC&printsec=frontcover&dq=wheel+of+health#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=12 August 2010}}\n* Miller, Katherine, 'Schooling Virtue: Education for 'Spiritual Development' in Megan Adamson Sijapati and Jessica Vantine Birkenholtz, eds., Religion and Modernity in the Himalaya (London: Routledge, 2016).\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Hunza Valley}}\n\n* http://emergingpakistan.gov.pk/travel/place-to-visit/gilgit-baltistan/hunza-valley/\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category: Valleys of Gilgit-Baltistan]]\n[[Category: Hunza]]\n[[Category: History of Gilgit Agency]]\n[[Category: Hindu Kush]]\n[[Category: Himalayas]]\n[[Category: Regions of Pakistan]]\n[[Category: Landslides in 2010]]\n[[Category: Valleys of Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the article about the former princely state|Hunza (princely state)}}\n{{original research|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox valley\n| name               = Hunza Valley\n| other_name         = \n| native_name        = \u06c1\u0646\u0632\u0648\n| native_name_lang   = bsk\n| translation        = \n| photo              = File:Rakaposhi, Nagar GB (Pakistan).jpg\n| photo_caption      = The {{Convert|7788|m}} tall [[Rakaposhi]] mountain towers over Hunza\n<!--    MAP     -->\n| map                = Gilgit Baltistan#Pakistan\n| map_image          = \n| map_caption        = \n<!--  Location  -->\n| location           = \n| country            = {{flagicon|Pakistan}} [[Pakistan]]\n| region             = {{flagicon|Gilgit-Baltistan}} [[Gilgit-Baltistan]]\n| state              = \n| district           = [[Hunza District]]\n| city               = \n| relief             = \n| label              = \n| label_position     = \n| coordinates        = {{coord|36.316942|N|74.649900|E|display=inline}} \n| coordinates_ref    = <ref>{{cite web |title=Hunza on Google Maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Hunza+Valley/ |website=Google Maps |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n<!-- Statistics -->  \n| elevation          = \n| elevation_m        = \n| elevation_ft       = \n| elevation_ref      = \n| length             = \n| length_mi          = \n| length_km          = \n| length_orientation = \n| length_note        = \n| width              = \n| width_mi           = \n| width_km           = \n| width_orientation  = \n| width_note         = \n| area               = \n| area_mi2           = \n| area_km2           = \n| depth              = \n| depth_ft           = \n| depth_m            = \n| type               = \n| age                = \n| border             = \n| topo               = \n| traversed          = \n| river              = \n<!-- Below --> \n| footnotes          = \n| embed              = \n}}\n'''Hunza''' ({{lang-bsk|\u06c1\u0646\u0632\u0648}}, [[Wakhi language|Wakhi]]: \"{{lang|wbl|shina}}\", {{lang-ur|{{nq|\u06c1\u0646\u0632\u06c1}}}}) is a mountainous valley in the [[Gilgit-Baltistan|Gilgit-Baltistan region]] of [[Pakistan]]. Hunza is situated in the extreme northern part of Pakistan, bordering with the [[Wakhan Corridor]] of [[Afghanistan]] and the [[Xinjiang|Xinjiang region]] of [[China]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Mountainous Valley situated in extreme northern part of Pakistan |url=https://www.dreamstime.com/hunza-mountainous-valley-gilgit-baltistan-region-pakistan-hunza-situated-extreme-northern-part-image107691385 |website=www.dreamstime.com |accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Hunza valley is situated at an elevation of 2,438 meters (7,999 feet).  Geographicaly, Hunza consists of three regions, Upper Hunza ([[Gojal]]), Central Hunza (\"Hunza Valley\") and Lower Hunza (\"Shinaki\"). \n\n== History ==\n{{main|State of Hunza}}\n[[File: Baltit Fort, Karimabad, Hunza, Gilgit Baltistan.jpg|thumb|[[Baltit Fort]], the former residence of the Mirs of Hunza]]\nHunza was formerly a [[princely state]] bordering  [[Xinjiang]] (autonomous region of China) to the northeast and [[Pamir Mountains|Pamir]] to the northwest, which survived until 1974, when it was finally dissolved by [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]].  The state bordered the [[Gilgit Agency]] to the south and the former princely state of [[Nagar (princely state)|Nagar]] to the east. The state capital was the town of Baltit (also known as [[Karimabad (Hunza)|Karimabad]]); another old settlement is [[Ganish Village]] which means \"ancient gold\" village. Hunza was an independent principality for more than 900 years until the [[British Raj|British]] gained control of it and the neighboring valley of Nagar between 1889 and 1891 through military conquest. The then [[Tham (title)|Mir/Tham]] (ruler), branch of [[Katoor Dynasty|Katur Dynasty]], Safdar Khan of Hunza fled to [[Kashghar]] in China and sought what would now be called political asylum.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Valley|first1=Hunza|title=Hunza Valley|url=http://www.skardu.pk/hunza-valley/|website=www.skardu.pk|publisher=Skardu.pk|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Mir/Tham===\n{{main|Mir of Hunza}}\n\nAn account wrote by John Biddulph in his book ''[[Tribes of the Hindoo Koosh]]'' {{cquote|The ruling family of Hunza is called Ayesha (heavenly). The two states of [[Hunza (princely state)|Hunza]] and [[Nagar (princely state)|Nagar]] were formerly one, ruled by a branch of the Shahreis, the ruling family of [[Gilgit]], whose seat of government was Nager. First muslim came to Hunza-Nagar Valley some 1000 years (At the time of Imam Isl\u0101m Sh\u0101h 30th Imam Ismaili Muslims). After the introduction of [[Islam]] to Gilgit, married a daughter of Trakhan of [[Gilgit]], who bore him twin sons, named Moghlot and Girkis. From the former, the present ruling family of Nager is descended. The twins are said to have shown hostility to one another from birth. Thereupon their father, unable to settle the question of succession, divided his state between them, giving Girkis the north/west, and to Moghlot the south/east bank of the river.<ref>Tribes of the Hindoo Koosh by John Biddulph page 26</ref>}}\n\n===2010 landslide===\nIn 2010, a landslide blocked the river and created [[Attabad Lake]] (also called shishket Lake), resulting in 20 deaths and 8 injuries and has effectively blocked about {{convert|26|km}} of the [[Karakoram Highway]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Waheed |first1=Abdul |title=The Attabad Landslide Disaster |url=https://pamirtimes.net/2013/01/04/the-attabad-landslide-disaster/ |accessdate=12 October 2019 |publisher=Pamir Times |date=4 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=SHISHKET LAKE CRISES \u2013 2010 \u2013 CHRONOLOGY OF EVENTS |url=http://www.ndma.gov.pk/new/aboutus/SHISHKET_lake_2010.pdf |website=ndma.gov.pk |publisher=[[National Disaster Management Authority (Pakistan)|NDMA]] |accessdate=12 October 2019 |date=27 July 2010}}</ref> The new lake extends {{convert|30|km|mi}} and rose to a depth of {{convert|400|ft|m}} when it was formed as the Hunza River backed up.<ref name=\"fourworlds_HiMaT_2013\">{{cite web | url=http://www.fourworlds.ca/documents/ASecondGreenRevolution.pdf | title=Needed: a second green revolution in Hunza | publisher=HiMaT | date=May 2013 | accessdate=26 November 2015 | pages=4 | author1=Michael Bopp | author2=Judie Bopp}} Karakorum Area Development Organization (KADO), Aliabad</ref> The landslide completely covered sections of the Karakoram Highway.<ref name=\"fourworlds_HiMaT_2013\" />\n\n===2018 Rescue mission===\n[[File:Hunza Tunnel.jpg|thumb|right|Tunnel]]\nOn 1 July 2018, [[Pakistan Army]] pilots in a daring mission rescued 3 foreign mountaineers stuck in snow avalanche at above the height of {{Convert|19000|ft}} on [[Ultar Sar|Ultar Sar Peak]] near Hunza. The perilous weather conditions had made it difficult for the Army helicopter to go forth with a rescue operation on the {{Convert|7,388|m}} high [[Ultar Sar]]. But they completed it. Bruce Normand and Timothy Miller from [[United Kingdom|UK]] successfully rescued alive while their companion Christian Huber from [[Austria]] had succumbed to avalanche.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pakistan Army Pilots rescued 3 foreign mountaineers |url=https://en.dailypakistan.com.pk/headline/pakistan-army-rescues-avalanche-stricken-british-mountaineers-in-hunza-valley/ |website=en.dailypakistan.com.pk |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mountainers News on Thenews.com.pk |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/336019-pakistan-army-rescues-two-british-mountaineers-stranded-on |website=www.thenews.com.pk |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nBritain's High Commissioner [[Thomas Drew (diplomat)|Thomas Drew]] in [[Pakistan]] termed the mission \u201cremarkable and dangerous\u201d and said:\n\n\u201c''Our gratitude to the [[Pakistan Army]] pilots who rescued two British climbers trapped by an avalanche on [[Ultar Sar|Ultar Sar Peak]] near Hunza. Our thoughts with their Austrian fellow climber who died\u201d''.\n<ref>{{cite web |title=Britain's High Commissioner in Pakistan admired Pak Army Pilots for rescued the two British Climbers |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/07/01/british-mountaineers-rescued-deadly-pakistan-avalanche-19000ft/ |website=www.telegraph.co.uk |accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Major General Asif Ghafoor also tweeted about it |url=https://www.forces.net/news/british-climbers-rescued-pakistan-army |website=www.forces.net |accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== People ==\n{{main|Hunza people}}\nThe local languages spoken include [[Burushaski]], [[Wakhi language|Wakhi]] and [[Shina language|Shina]]. The literacy rate of the Hunza valley is more than 95%.<ref name=\"education dawn\">{{cite news|url=http://archives.dawn.com/archives/29975|title=Hunza disaster and schools|first=Shahid|last=Siddiqui|work=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]]|accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> The historical area of Hunza and present northern Pakistan has had, over the centuries, mass migrations, conflicts and resettling of tribes and ethnicities, of which the [[Shina people|Dardic Shina]] race is the most prominent in regional history. People of the region have recounted their historical traditions down the generations. The Hunza Valley is also home to some [[Wakhi people|Wakhi]], who migrated there from northeastern Afghanistan beginning in the nineteenth century onwards.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Arts and Crafts of the Hunza Valley in Pakistan: Living Traditions in the Karakoram|last=Frembgen Wasim|first=Jurgen|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2017|isbn=978-0-19-940520-6|location=Karachi|pages=1}}</ref>\n\nThe longevity of Hunza people has been noted by some,<ref name=\"Wrench1938\">{{Cite book |year=1938 |author=Wrench, Dr Guy T |title=The Wheel of Health: A Study of the Hunza People and the Keys to Health |series=2009 reprint |place= |publisher=Review Press |isbn=978-0-9802976-6-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lMfSuHgabYoC&printsec=frontcover&dq=wheel+of+health#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=12 August 2010 }}</ref> but others refute this as a [[Longevity myths|longevity myth]] and cite a life expectancy of 110 years for men and 122 for women with a high standard deviation.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C02E2D9173CF93AA1575AC0A960958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2 | work=The New York Times | title=The Optimists Are Right | first=John | last=Tierney | date=29 September 1996}}</ref> There is no evidence that Hunza life expectancy is significantly above the average of poor, isolated regions of Pakistan. Claims of health and long life were almost always based solely on the statements by the local mir (king). An author who had significant and sustained contact with Burusho people, John Clark, reported that they were overall unhealthy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblelife.org/hunza.htm|title=Hunza \u2013 The Truth, Myths, and Lies About the Health and Diet of the \"Long-Lived\" People of Hunza, Pakistan, Hunza Bread and Pie Recipes.|website=www.biblelife.org}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[State of Hunza|State of Hunza (former)]]\n* [[Hunza\u2013Nagar District]]\n* [[Bagrot Valley]]\n* [[Naltar Valley]]\n* [[Shamanism in Hunza]]\n* [[Northern Areas|Northern Areas (former)]]\n* [[Silk Road transmission of Buddhism]]\n* [[Karakoram Highway]]\n* [[Karakoram Mountains]]\n* [[Neelam Valley]]\n* [[Kalasha Valley]]\n* [[Kaghan Valley]]\n* [[Nagar Valley]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Kreutzmann, Hermann, ''Karakoram in Transition: Culture, Development, and Ecology in the Hunza Valley'', Oxford University Press, 2006. {{ISBN|978-0-19-547210-3}}\n* Leitner, G. W. (1893): ''Dardistan in 1866, 1886 and 1893: Being An Account of the History, Religions, Customs, Legends, Fables and Songs of Gilgit, Chilas, Kandia (Gabrial) Yasin, Chitral, Hunza, Nagar and other parts of the Hindukush, as also a supplement to the second edition of The Hunza and Nagar Handbook. And An Epitome of Part III of the author\u2019s \u201cThe Languages and Races of Dardistan.\u201d'' First Reprint 1978. Manjusri Publishing House, New Delhi.\n* Lorimer, Lt. Col. D.L.R. ''Folk Tales of Hunza''. 1st edition 1935, Oslo. Three volumes. Vol. II, republished by the Institute of Folk Heritage, Islamabad. 1981.\n* Sidkey, M. H. \"Shamans and Mountain Spirits in Hunza.\" ''Asian Folklore Studies'', Vol. 53, No. 1 (1994), pp.&nbsp;67\u201396.\n* [https://hisamullah.wordpress.com/2012/04/29/tarikh-e-ehd-e-ateeq-e-riasat-e-hunza-english-translation/ History of Ancient Era Hunza State] By Haji Qudratullah Beg English Translation By Lt Col (Rtd) Saadullah Beg, TI(M)\n* {{citation |year=1938 |author=Wrench, Dr Guy T |title=The Wheel of Health: A Study of the Hunza People and the Keys to Health |series=2009 reprint |place= |publisher=Review Press |isbn=978-0-9802976-6-9 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=lMfSuHgabYoC&printsec=frontcover&dq=wheel+of+health#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=12 August 2010}}\n* Miller, Katherine, 'Schooling Virtue: Education for 'Spiritual Development' in Megan Adamson Sijapati and Jessica Vantine Birkenholtz, eds., Religion and Modernity in the Himalaya (London: Routledge, 2016).\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Hunza Valley}}\n\n* http://emergingpakistan.gov.pk/travel/place-to-visit/gilgit-baltistan/hunza-valley/\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category: Valleys of Gilgit-Baltistan]]\n[[Category: Hunza]]\n[[Category: History of Gilgit Agency]]\n[[Category: Hindu Kush]]\n[[Category: Himalayas]]\n[[Category: Regions of Pakistan]]\n[[Category: Landslides in 2010]]\n[[Category: Valleys of Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "Shamsalibe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2010 landslide", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hunza_Valley"}
{"title_page": "Ed Westwick", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Ed Westwick\n| image = Ed Westwick July 2010 cropped.jpg\n| caption = Westwick in July 2010\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1987|6|27}}\n| birth_place = {{nowrap|[[Hammersmith]], [[London]], England}}\n|nationality =British \n| occupation = {{Flat list|\n* Actor\n* musician\n}}\n| years_active = 2006\u2013present\n}}\n'''Edward Jack Peter Westwick'''<ref name=\"Birth Record\">{{cite web|url=https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QV4V-D8SZ|title=Person Details for Edward Jack P Westwick, \"England & Wales Births, 1837-2006\"|website=[[FamilySearch]]}}</ref> (born 27 June 1987)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/06/27/Famous-birthdays-for-June-27-Vera-Wang-Khloe-Kardashian/7961561311112/|title=Famous birthdays for June 27: Vera Wang, Khloe Kardashian|agency=[[United Press International]]|date=June 27, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2019|url-status=live|quote=Actor Ed Westwick in 1987 (age 32)}}</ref> is an English actor and musician, best known for his role as [[Chuck Bass]] on [[The CW]]'s teen television drama series ''[[Gossip Girl]]'' alongside co-stars [[Blake Lively]] and [[Leighton Meester]]. He made his feature film debut in ''[[Children of Men]]'' (2006) and has since appeared in the films ''[[Breaking and Entering (film)|Breaking and Entering]]'' (2006), ''[[Son of Rambow]]'' (2007), ''[[S. Darko]]'' (2009), ''[[Chalet Girl]]'' (2011), ''[[J. Edgar]]'' (2011), ''[[Romeo & Juliet (2013 film)|Romeo and Juliet]]'' (2013), ''[[Bone in the Throat]]'' (2015), ''[[Freaks of Nature (film)|Freaks of Nature]]'' (2015), and ''[[Billionaire Ransom]]'' (2016). He currently plays Vincent Swan in the [[BBC Two]] television comedy series ''[[White Gold (TV series)|White Gold]]'' (2017).\nit is believed he had a relationship with maria sim\u00f5es some years ago, but they decided to hide it from the public.\n\n==Early life==\nWestwick was born in [[Hammersmith]], London,<ref name=\"Birth Record\"/> and raised in [[Stevenage]], [[Hertfordshire]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sykes|first=Pandora|title=Ed Westwick's My London|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/ed-westwicks-my-london-6532553.html|website=[[London Evening Standard]]|accessdate=16 January 2014|date=4 November 2010|quote=I was raised in Stevenage.}}</ref> He is the third and youngest child of Carole (n\u00e9e Blenkiron),<ref name=\"Birth Record\"/> an educational psychologist, and Peter Westwick, a university lecturer.<ref name=\"HuffPo\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2008/04/27/meet-ed-westwick-british_n_98832.html|title=Meet Ed Westwick: British Born Star Of \"Gossip Girl\"|newspaper=[[HuffPost]]|accessdate=7 December 2011|date=27 April 2008}}</ref> He has two older brothers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.okmagazine.com/uncategorized/ed-westwick-got-bullied-around/|title=Ed Westwick Got Bullied Around|website=[[OK!]]|first=Valerie|last=Nome|date=7 May 2008}}</ref> He began music lessons and attended a Saturday morning drama school from the age of six.<ref name=\"book\">{{cite book|last=Kaye|first=Liz|title=Gossip Boys: The Double Unauthorised Biography of Ed Westwick and Chace Crawford|url=https://books.google.com/?id=nt_kNgsBfu0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Gossip+Boys:+The+Double+Unauthorised+Biography+of+Ed+Westwick+and+Chace+Crawford#|publisher=Virgin Books|pages=10\u201312|isbn=978-0-7535-4028-2|date=2011-09-29}}</ref> Westwick was educated at [[The Barclay School]] and [[North Hertfordshire College]], where he took [[A-level]]s in business, law, and communication.<ref name=\"book\"/> He later trained at the [[National Youth Theatre]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ed Westwick: People.com|url=http://www.people.com/people/ed_westwick|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=8 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alumni|url=http://www.nyt.org.uk/alumni|website=[[National Youth Theatre]]|accessdate=8 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Acting===\nWestwick made his film debut in ''[[Breaking and Entering (film)|Breaking and Entering]]'' (2006), following an open audition casting call sent to the National Youth Theatre.<ref>{{cite web|title=Transcript: Anjali Rao interviews \"Gossip Girl\" actor about his character, his other projects, his beginnings, and his future.|url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1107/20/ta.01.html|website=[[CNN]]|accessdate=8 August 2015|date=20 July 2011}}</ref> He went on to guest star in the British television series ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'' as Holden, ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' as Johnny Cullin, and ''[[Afterlife (TV series)|Afterlife]]'' as Darren. He also had a minor role in the film ''[[Children of Men]]'' (2006).{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 2007, Westwick appeared in the film ''[[Son of Rambow]]'' and was cast as [[Chuck Bass]] in [[The CW]]'s teen drama series ''[[Gossip Girl]]'', based on [[Gossip Girl (novel series)|the book series of the same name]] by [[Cecily von Ziegesar]]. Westwick said of his casting, \"There wasn't much work in the UK. I was only in LA for a month and I got this show. It's changed my life.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/2010/09/22/gossip-girls-ed-westwick-is-suited-to-the-english-gent-role-520447/|title=Gossip Girl's Ed Westwick is suited to the English gent role|website=[[Metro UK]]|date=22 September 2010|accessdate=23 June 2013}}</ref> For his portrayal of Chuck, he assumed an American accent, based on the character Carlton Banks from ''[[The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.details.com/celebrities-entertainment/cover-stars/200809/boys-of-gossip-girl?currentPage=4|title=Boys of Gossip Girl|website=[[Details (magazine)|Details]]|first=Mark|last=Harris|date=November 2008|accessdate=23 June 2013}}</ref> As a result of the show's success, he was named one of 2008's Sexiest Men Alive by ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/package/gallery/0,,20237714_20241212_20545190,00.html|title=2008's Sexiest Men Alive \u2013 Ed Westwick|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=November 2008|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref> and appeared the following year on its \"100 Most Beautiful\" list with the whole cast of ''Gossip Girl''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/package/gallery/0,,20267544_20196426_20447788,00.html|title=World's Most Beautiful People \u2013 The Gossip Girl Cast|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=6 December 2011|year=2009}}</ref> Westwick earned the 2008 and 2009 awards for Best TV Villain at the [[Teen Choice Awards]], and was named Breakthrough Talent by ''[[GQ]]'' in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/men-of-the-year/home/winners-2010-unseen/ed-westwick-exclusive-photos/top-hat-on-cane|title=GQ Men Of The Year 2010 \u2013 Breakthrough Talent: Ed Westwick|website=[[GQ]]|first=Sanjiv|last=Bhattacharya|date=7 September 2010|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' also named Westwick's character Chuck Bass number one in their \"Best Dressed TV Characters of 2008\" list (tied with [[Leighton Meester]]'s character [[Blair Waldorf]]), as well as in their \"Best Performances\" list alongside co-star Meester.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20162677_20164091_20243883_9,00.html|title=The Best & Worst of 2008|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ed Westwick July 2010 d.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Westwick on the set of ''[[Gossip Girl]]'' in 2010]]\nIn 2008, Westwick became the new face of [[K-Swiss]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nymag.com/daily/fashion/2008/11/ed_westwick_lands_k-swiss_camp.html|title=Ed Westwick Lands K-Swiss Campaign|website=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|first=Amy|last=Odell|date=5 November 2008|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref> That same year, he appeared as Joey in the horror film ''[[100 Feet]]''. In 2009, Westwick played the role of Randy Holt in the [[S. Darko|sequel]] to ''[[Donnie Darko]]'', directed by [[Chris Fisher]], and guest-starred in the third season of the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] original series ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]'', as Chris \"Balt\" Smith, a student who was fascinated with vampire literature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news-briefs.ew.com/2009/05/showtimes-calif.html/|title=Showtime's \"Californication\" adds Ed Westwick, Eva Amurri as season 3 guest stars|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Tanner|last=Stransky|date=1 May 2009|accessdate=30 June 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504061756/http://news-briefs.ew.com/2009/05/showtimes-calif.html|archivedate=4 May 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In May 2009, he was attached to play Heathcliff in the film adaptation of ''[[Wuthering Heights (2011 film)|Wuthering Heights]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/article/VR1118003630?refCatId=13|title=Cast taken to new 'Heights'|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Ali|last=Jaafar|date=14 May 2009|accessdate=12 April 2012}}</ref> However, in January 2010, director [[Peter Webber]] left the project, which was then passed into the hands of [[Andrea Arnold]]. This directing change caused the roles to be recast.\n\nIn 2010, Westwick starred in the [[McHenry Brothers]] short film ''The Commuter'', which was shot on a [[Nokia N8]] smartphone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/the-commuter-reveals-the-potential-of-new-technology-2112931.html|title=The Commuter reveals the potential of new technology|website=[[The Independent]]|first=Jo|last=Caird|date=22 October 2010|accessdate=23 June 2013}}</ref> In January 2011, Westwick joined [[Clint Eastwood]]'s film ''[[J. Edgar]]'', a biopic about [[J. Edgar Hoover]], the controversial first director of the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2011/01/11/ed-westwick-j-edgar/|title=Ed Westwick cast in 'J. Edgar'|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Margaret|last=Lyons|date=11 January 2011|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref> That same year, he appeared in the romantic comedy ''[[Chalet Girl]]''. He co-narrated the audio book version of ''[[City of Fallen Angels]]'' by [[Cassandra Clare]] and also narrated Clare's second novel ''[[Clockwork Prince]]'' from ''[[The Infernal Devices]]'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2011/12/06/clockwork-prince-cassandra-clare-ed-westwick-interview/|title=EXCLUSIVE: 'Clockwork Prince' Author Cassandra Clare Interviews Audiobook Narrator Ed Westwick|website=[[MTV]]|first=Amy|last=Wilkinson|date=6 December 2011|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref> In mid-2011, Westwick became an international celebrity endorser for [[Penshoppe]], a local clothing brand in the [[Philippines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mb.com.ph/node/321192/ed-we|title=Ed Westwick works his 'Chuck Bass' to thrill Manila crowd|website=Manila Bulletin|first=Annie S.|last=Alejo|date=14 June 2011|accessdate=29 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/celeb/fashion/24738/actor-Ed-Westwick-will-be-in-Manila-to-shoot-new-campaign-of-local-clothing-brand|title=Gossip Girl actor Ed Westwick will be in Manila to shoot new campaign of local clothing brand|website=Philippine Entertainment Portal|first=Nerisa|last=Almo|date=28 May 2011|accessdate=29 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307035009/http://www.pep.ph/celeb/fashion/24738/actor-Ed-Westwick-will-be-in-Manila-to-shoot-new-campaign-of-local-clothing-brand|archive-date=7 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe next co-starred in the film adaptation of ''[[Romeo & Juliet (2013 film)|Romeo & Juliet]]'' as the main [[antagonist]] and Juliet's cousin, [[Tybalt]]. The film was released on 11 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/ed-westwick-romeo-and-juliet/92444/|title=Ed Westwick to Play Tybalt in ROMEO AND JULIET|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|first=Adam|last=Chitwood|date=23 May 2011|accessdate=15 January 2012}}</ref> Westwick then portrayed the lead role in the film adaptation of [[Anthony Bourdain]]'s novel ''[[Bone in the Throat]]'', which premiered at [[South by Southwest]] on 14 March 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2013/05/cannes-briefs-wild-bunch-ups-carole-baraton-elle-driver-gets-ugly-studiocanal-selling-100-year-old-man-490792/|title=Ed Westwick Has A 'Bone In The Throat'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=6 May 2013}}</ref> Westwick then co-starred in the horror comedy film ''[[Freaks of Nature (film)|Freaks of Nature]]'', which was released on 30 October 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/movies/column-post/gossip-girl-alum-ed-westwick-may-sink-his-fangs-sonys-kitchen-sink-exclusive-110856|title='Gossip Girl' Alum Ed Westwick in Negotiations to Star in Sony's 'Kitchen Sink' (Exclusive)|website=[[TheWrap]]|first=Jeff|last=Sneider|date=15 August 2013|accessdate=16 September 2013}}</ref> In March 2015, he joined the cast of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s short-lived crime drama series ''[[Wicked City (TV series)|Wicked City]]'' as Kent Grainger, a sadistic Sunset Strip serial killer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/gossip-girl-alum-play-creepy-781019|title='Gossip Girl' Alum to Play Creepy Murderer in ABC Pilot|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Michael|last=O'Connell|date=12 March 2015}}</ref> The series was cancelled after airing 3 episodes, but was picked up by [[Hulu]] to air the remaining 5 episodes. Westwick was next seen in [[Jim Gillespie (director)|Jim Gillespie]]'s ''[[Billionaire Ransom]]'', released on 19 August 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/ed-westwick-dominic-sherwood-join-jim-gillespies-take-down-exclusive-1201181277/|title=Ed Westwick, Dominic Sherwood Join Jim Gillespie's 'Take Down' (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=John|last=Hopewell|date=14 May 2014|accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref> and stars in the thriller ''[[The Crash (2017 film)|The Crash]]'', released on 13 January 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/frank-grillo-jekyll-island-minnie-driver-1200775773/|title='The Butler' Producer Sets up Next Pic Starring Frank Grillo and Minnie Driver (EXCLUSIVE)|first=Justin|last=Kroll|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=1 March 2015|date=2013-10-29}}</ref>\n\nWestwick will next star in ''Me, You, Madness'' co-starring and directed by [[Louise Linton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/me-you-madness-first-look-image-of-pic-from-writer-director-star-louise-linton-1202597295/|title=\u2018Me, You, Madness\u2019: First-Look Image Of Pic From Writer-Director-Star Louise Linton|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Erik|last=Pederson|date=April 16, 2019|accessdate=December 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nWestwick was a member of the British band The Filthy Youth.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pressler|first1=Jessica|last2=Rovzar|first2=Chris|url=https://nymag.com/arts/tv/features/46225/|title=The Genius of Gossip Girl|date=21 April 2008|website=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]}}</ref> The [[Punk rock|punk]] band, formed in 2006, was inspired by the [[Rolling Stones]], [[The Doors]] and [[Kings of Leon]]. The songs \"Come Flash All You Ladies\" and \"Orange\" were both featured in an episode of ''Gossip Girl''. The band consisted of fellow countrymen Benjamin Lewis Allingham (guitar), Jimmy Wright (guitar), Tom Bastiani (bass), and John Vooght (drummer). <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1595447/20080923/story.jhtml|title='Gossip Girl' Stars Leighton Meester, Ed Westwick Parlay TV Success Into Music Careers|first=Jocelyn|last=Vena|date=24 September 2008|website=[[MTV]]|accessdate=24 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWestwick shared an apartment with his ''Gossip Girl'' co-star [[Chace Crawford]] in the [[Chelsea, Manhattan|Chelsea]] neighbourhood of [[Manhattan]] from the beginning of the series in 2007 until July 2009, when Crawford moved out.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Leonard|first1=Elizabeth|last2=Garcia|first2=Jennifer|title=Chace Crawford Bachelor No. 1|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20287137,00.html|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=23 June 2013|date=29 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Tartaglione|first=Nancy|title=Chace Crawford Moves Out of Ed Westwick's Apartment|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/chace-crawford-moves-out-of-ed-westwicks-apartment-2009137|website=[[Us Weekly]]|accessdate=23 June 2013|date=13 July 2009}}</ref> He was in a relationship with his Gossip Girl co-star [[Jessica Szohr]] in 2009.<ref>https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/gossip-girl-jessixa-szohr-dating-ed-westwick-can-be-awkward-20092812/</ref> \n\nWestwick supports [[Chelsea F.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/celebs-on-sunday/2009/05/03/ed-westwick-i-can-be-a-real-bitch-people-know-when-to-stay-away-115875-21316088/|title=Ed Westwick: 'I can be a real bitch \u2013 people know when to stay away'|website=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=3 May 2009|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/funfare/exclusivesarticle.aspx?articleid=693196&publicationsubcategoryid=70|title=Ed Westwick: Television's Most Loved 'Bad Boy'|last=Lo|first=Ricky|website=[[The Philippine Star]]|date=5 June 2011|accessdate=5 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111202020/http://www.philstar.com/funfare/ExclusivesArticle.aspx?articleId=693196&publicationSubCategoryId=70|archive-date=11 November 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Sexual assault claims===\nIn November 2017, allegations were separately made by three women: Kristina Cohen, Rachel Eck, and Aur\u00e9lie Wynn. Cohen and Wynn made claims of  rape, and Eck claims of sexual assault. All three claim the incidents occurred in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ed-westwick-accused-rape-actor-denies-claim-1055474|title='Gossip Girl' Star Ed Westwick Accused of Rape, Actor Denies Claim|date=7 November 2017|last=Gardner|first=Chris|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/ed-westwick-second-accuser-sexual-assault-claim-1202204751/|title=Ed Westwick Calls Rape Accusations \"Provably Untrue\" After Second Woman Comes Forward \u2013 Update|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=Robb|first=David|date=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/ed-westwick-third-accuser-sexual-assault-rachel-eck|title=Third Woman Accuses Ed Westwick of Sexual Assault|website=Vanity Fair|last=Bradley|first=Laura|date=15 November 2017}}</ref> Westwick issued a statement describing the allegations from Cohen and Wynn as \"unverified and provably untrue\" and further stated: \"I have never forced myself in any manner, on any woman. I certainly have never committed rape\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/gossip-girl-actor-ed-westwick-accused-of-raping-actress-w511210 |title='Gossip Girl' Actor Ed Westwick Denies Raping Actress Kristina Cohen |last=Chen |first=Joyce |date=7 November 2017 |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/ed-westwick-second-accuser-sexual-assault-claim-1202204751 |title=Second Woman Accuses Ed Westwick Of Sexual Assault |last=Robb |first=David |date=8 November 2017 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/ed-westwick-sexual-assault_us_5a04313ae4b0f76b05c38eb3|title=Second Woman Accuses Actor Ed Westwick Of Sexual Assault|newspaper=[[Huff Post|Huffington Post]]|date=9 November 2017|last1=Dicker|first1=Ron}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/ed-westwick-third-woman-accusations-sexual-assault-1202209295/|title=Third Woman Accuses Ed Westwick Of Sexual Assault|first=David|last=Robb|date=15 November 2017|publisher=|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/mbvd/a-third-woman-says-gossip-girl-star-ed-westwick-sexually|title=A Third Woman Says \"Gossip Girl\" Star Ed Westwick Sexually Assaulted Her|website=BuzzFeed News|date=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/ed-westwick-lapd-investigation-rape-allegations-actress-1202203757/|title=LAPD Investigating Rape Allegations Against Ed Westwick|first=David|last=Robb|date=7 November 2017|publisher=|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/ed-westwick-rape-latest-lapd-investigate-kristina-cohen-gossip-girl-a8043176.html|title=Ed Westwick rape allegation 'being investigated by LAPD'|publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=8 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-44985583|title=Ed Westwick will not be prosecuted in US|date=27 July 2018|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com|work=BBC News}}</ref>\nIn July 2018, the office of the Los Angeles District Attorney announced that Westwick would not be prosecuted regarding the claims of rape and sexual assault. Prosecutors said witnesses identified by the first two alleged victims were \"not able to provide information that would enable the prosecution to prove either incident beyond a reasonable doubt\", with prosecutors unable to contact the third claimant. Prosecutors also noted additional claims made by other individuals would not be looked into due to being outside the statute of limitations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-44985583|title=Ed Westwick will not be prosecuted in US|date=27 July 2018|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe allegations resulted in the re-shooting of scenes involving Westwick in the BBC adaptation of the [[Agatha Christie]]'s ''[[Ordeal by Innocence (miniseries)|Ordeal By Innocence]]'' with [[Christian Cooke]], and series two of ''[[White Gold (TV series)|White Gold]]'' being \"paused\". Westwick has stated he is disappointed with the actions of the BBC due to the ongoing investigations, legal processes, and the unverified nature of the claims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-42577505|title=Ed Westwick removed from BBC Agatha Christie drama Ordeal By Innocence|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=5 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/01/05/ed-westwick-replaced-sexual-assault-allegations-ordeal-by-innocence |title=Ed Westwick replaced in Agatha Christie drama following sexual assault claims |last=Romano |first=Nick |date=5 January 2018 |publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/ed-westwick-bbc-ordeal-by-innocence-white-gold-1202205604/ |title=BBC Drops Ed Westwick Drama 'Ordeal By Innocence', Halts Appearance In 'White Gold' |last=Evans |first=Greg |date=10 November 2017 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Children of Men]]''\n| Alex\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Breaking and Entering (film)|Breaking and Entering]]''\n| Zoran\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Son of Rambow]]''\n| Lawrence Carter\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[100 Feet]]''\n| Joey\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[S. Darko]]''\n| Randy Holt\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[McHenry Brothers|The Commuter]]''\n| Bellboy in Lift\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Chalet Girl]]''\n| Jonny Madsen\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[J. Edgar]]''\n| Agent Smith\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Romeo & Juliet (2013 film)|Romeo & Juliet]]''\n| [[Tybalt]]\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Last Flight (film)|Last Flight]]''\n| Charles Gillis\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Bone in the Throat]]''\n| Will Reeves\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Freaks of Nature (film)|Freaks of Nature]]''\n| Milan Pinache\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Billionaire Ransom]]''\n| Billy Speck\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Crash (2017 film)|The Crash]]''\n| Ben Collins\n|\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''Me, You, Madness''\n| Tyler Jones\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]''\n| Holden Edwards\n| Episode: \"Young Mothers Do Have 'Em\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''\n| Johnny Cullin\n| Episode: \"Family Matters\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Afterlife (TV series)|Afterlife]]''\n| Darren\n| Episode: \"Roadside Bouquets\"\n|-\n| 2007\u20132012\n| ''[[Gossip Girl]]''\n| [[Chuck Bass|Charles \"Chuck\" Bass]]\n| Main character; 117 episodes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]''\n| Chris \"Balt\" Smith\n| Episode: \"The Land of Rape and Honey\"\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Wicked City (TV series)|Wicked City]]''\n| Kent Grainger\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Family Guy]]''\n| Football Player / Wedding Officiant (voice)\n| Episode: \"[[The Finer Strings]]\"\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Snatch (TV series)|Snatch]]''\n| Sonny Castillo\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\u20132019\n| ''[[White Gold (TV series)|White Gold]]''\n| Vincent Swan\n| 12 episodes\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Artist\n|-\n| 2018\n| \"Give Me Your Hand\"\n| Himself\n| Shannon K\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2008\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice TV Breakout Star \u2013 Male\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''[[Gossip Girl]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice TV \u2013 Villain|Choice TV \u2013 Villain]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2009\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Young Hollywood Awards]]\n| Young Hollywood Breakthrough \u2013 Male\n| Himself\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Breakthrough Performance \u2013 Male\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''Gossip Girl''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Teen Choice Awards\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Choice TV \u2013 Villain\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2011\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2012\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice TV Actor Drama|Choice TV Actor \u2013 Drama]]\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|2067953}}\n* [http://popgurls.com/2007/10/17/popgurls-interview-gossip-girls-ed-westwick-2/ PopGurls Interview: Ed Westwick]\n\n{{Teen Choice Award Choice TV Villain}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Westwick, Ed}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n[[Category:Audiobook narrators]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male models]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English rock singers]]\n[[Category:English singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:National Youth Theatre members]]\n[[Category:People from Chelsea, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:People from Hammersmith]]\n[[Category:People from Stevenage]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Ed Westwick\n| image = Ed Westwick July 2010 cropped.jpg\n| caption = Westwick in July 2010\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1987|6|27}}\n| birth_place = {{nowrap|[[Hammersmith]], [[London]], England}}\n|nationality =British \n| occupation = {{Flat list|\n* Actor\n* musician\n}}\n| years_active = 2006\u2013present\n}}\n'''Edward Jack Peter Westwick'''<ref name=\"Birth Record\">{{cite web|url=https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QV4V-D8SZ|title=Person Details for Edward Jack P Westwick, \"England & Wales Births, 1837-2006\"|website=[[FamilySearch]]}}</ref> (born 27 June 1987)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.upi.com/Entertainment_News/2019/06/27/Famous-birthdays-for-June-27-Vera-Wang-Khloe-Kardashian/7961561311112/|title=Famous birthdays for June 27: Vera Wang, Khloe Kardashian|agency=[[United Press International]]|date=June 27, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2019|url-status=live|quote=Actor Ed Westwick in 1987 (age 32)}}</ref> is an English actor and musician, best known for his role as [[Chuck Bass]] on [[The CW]]'s teen television drama series ''[[Gossip Girl]]'' alongside co-stars [[Blake Lively]] and [[Leighton Meester]]. He made his feature film debut in ''[[Children of Men]]'' (2006) and has since appeared in the films ''[[Breaking and Entering (film)|Breaking and Entering]]'' (2006), ''[[Son of Rambow]]'' (2007), ''[[S. Darko]]'' (2009), ''[[Chalet Girl]]'' (2011), ''[[J. Edgar]]'' (2011), ''[[Romeo & Juliet (2013 film)|Romeo and Juliet]]'' (2013), ''[[Bone in the Throat]]'' (2015), ''[[Freaks of Nature (film)|Freaks of Nature]]'' (2015), and ''[[Billionaire Ransom]]'' (2016). He currently plays Vincent Swan in the [[BBC Two]] television comedy series ''[[White Gold (TV series)|White Gold]]'' (2017).\n\n==Early life==\nWestwick was born in [[Hammersmith]], London,<ref name=\"Birth Record\"/> and raised in [[Stevenage]], [[Hertfordshire]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sykes|first=Pandora|title=Ed Westwick's My London|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/ed-westwicks-my-london-6532553.html|website=[[London Evening Standard]]|accessdate=16 January 2014|date=4 November 2010|quote=I was raised in Stevenage.}}</ref> He is the third and youngest child of Carole (n\u00e9e Blenkiron),<ref name=\"Birth Record\"/> an educational psychologist, and Peter Westwick, a university lecturer.<ref name=\"HuffPo\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2008/04/27/meet-ed-westwick-british_n_98832.html|title=Meet Ed Westwick: British Born Star Of \"Gossip Girl\"|newspaper=[[HuffPost]]|accessdate=7 December 2011|date=27 April 2008}}</ref> He has two older brothers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.okmagazine.com/uncategorized/ed-westwick-got-bullied-around/|title=Ed Westwick Got Bullied Around|website=[[OK!]]|first=Valerie|last=Nome|date=7 May 2008}}</ref> He began music lessons and attended a Saturday morning drama school from the age of six.<ref name=\"book\">{{cite book|last=Kaye|first=Liz|title=Gossip Boys: The Double Unauthorised Biography of Ed Westwick and Chace Crawford|url=https://books.google.com/?id=nt_kNgsBfu0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Gossip+Boys:+The+Double+Unauthorised+Biography+of+Ed+Westwick+and+Chace+Crawford#|publisher=Virgin Books|pages=10\u201312|isbn=978-0-7535-4028-2|date=2011-09-29}}</ref> Westwick was educated at [[The Barclay School]] and [[North Hertfordshire College]], where he took [[A-level]]s in business, law, and communication.<ref name=\"book\"/> He later trained at the [[National Youth Theatre]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ed Westwick: People.com|url=http://www.people.com/people/ed_westwick|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=8 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alumni|url=http://www.nyt.org.uk/alumni|website=[[National Youth Theatre]]|accessdate=8 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Acting===\nWestwick made his film debut in ''[[Breaking and Entering (film)|Breaking and Entering]]'' (2006), following an open audition casting call sent to the National Youth Theatre.<ref>{{cite web|title=Transcript: Anjali Rao interviews \"Gossip Girl\" actor about his character, his other projects, his beginnings, and his future.|url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1107/20/ta.01.html|website=[[CNN]]|accessdate=8 August 2015|date=20 July 2011}}</ref> He went on to guest star in the British television series ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'' as Holden, ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' as Johnny Cullin, and ''[[Afterlife (TV series)|Afterlife]]'' as Darren. He also had a minor role in the film ''[[Children of Men]]'' (2006).{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 2007, Westwick appeared in the film ''[[Son of Rambow]]'' and was cast as [[Chuck Bass]] in [[The CW]]'s teen drama series ''[[Gossip Girl]]'', based on [[Gossip Girl (novel series)|the book series of the same name]] by [[Cecily von Ziegesar]]. Westwick said of his casting, \"There wasn't much work in the UK. I was only in LA for a month and I got this show. It's changed my life.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/2010/09/22/gossip-girls-ed-westwick-is-suited-to-the-english-gent-role-520447/|title=Gossip Girl's Ed Westwick is suited to the English gent role|website=[[Metro UK]]|date=22 September 2010|accessdate=23 June 2013}}</ref> For his portrayal of Chuck, he assumed an American accent, based on the character Carlton Banks from ''[[The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.details.com/celebrities-entertainment/cover-stars/200809/boys-of-gossip-girl?currentPage=4|title=Boys of Gossip Girl|website=[[Details (magazine)|Details]]|first=Mark|last=Harris|date=November 2008|accessdate=23 June 2013}}</ref> As a result of the show's success, he was named one of 2008's Sexiest Men Alive by ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/package/gallery/0,,20237714_20241212_20545190,00.html|title=2008's Sexiest Men Alive \u2013 Ed Westwick|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=November 2008|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref> and appeared the following year on its \"100 Most Beautiful\" list with the whole cast of ''Gossip Girl''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/package/gallery/0,,20267544_20196426_20447788,00.html|title=World's Most Beautiful People \u2013 The Gossip Girl Cast|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=6 December 2011|year=2009}}</ref> Westwick earned the 2008 and 2009 awards for Best TV Villain at the [[Teen Choice Awards]], and was named Breakthrough Talent by ''[[GQ]]'' in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/men-of-the-year/home/winners-2010-unseen/ed-westwick-exclusive-photos/top-hat-on-cane|title=GQ Men Of The Year 2010 \u2013 Breakthrough Talent: Ed Westwick|website=[[GQ]]|first=Sanjiv|last=Bhattacharya|date=7 September 2010|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' also named Westwick's character Chuck Bass number one in their \"Best Dressed TV Characters of 2008\" list (tied with [[Leighton Meester]]'s character [[Blair Waldorf]]), as well as in their \"Best Performances\" list alongside co-star Meester.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20162677_20164091_20243883_9,00.html|title=The Best & Worst of 2008|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ed Westwick July 2010 d.jpg|200px|thumb|left|Westwick on the set of ''[[Gossip Girl]]'' in 2010]]\nIn 2008, Westwick became the new face of [[K-Swiss]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nymag.com/daily/fashion/2008/11/ed_westwick_lands_k-swiss_camp.html|title=Ed Westwick Lands K-Swiss Campaign|website=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|first=Amy|last=Odell|date=5 November 2008|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref> That same year, he appeared as Joey in the horror film ''[[100 Feet]]''. In 2009, Westwick played the role of Randy Holt in the [[S. Darko|sequel]] to ''[[Donnie Darko]]'', directed by [[Chris Fisher]], and guest-starred in the third season of the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] original series ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]'', as Chris \"Balt\" Smith, a student who was fascinated with vampire literature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news-briefs.ew.com/2009/05/showtimes-calif.html/|title=Showtime's \"Californication\" adds Ed Westwick, Eva Amurri as season 3 guest stars|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Tanner|last=Stransky|date=1 May 2009|accessdate=30 June 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504061756/http://news-briefs.ew.com/2009/05/showtimes-calif.html|archivedate=4 May 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In May 2009, he was attached to play Heathcliff in the film adaptation of ''[[Wuthering Heights (2011 film)|Wuthering Heights]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/article/VR1118003630?refCatId=13|title=Cast taken to new 'Heights'|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Ali|last=Jaafar|date=14 May 2009|accessdate=12 April 2012}}</ref> However, in January 2010, director [[Peter Webber]] left the project, which was then passed into the hands of [[Andrea Arnold]]. This directing change caused the roles to be recast.\n\nIn 2010, Westwick starred in the [[McHenry Brothers]] short film ''The Commuter'', which was shot on a [[Nokia N8]] smartphone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/the-commuter-reveals-the-potential-of-new-technology-2112931.html|title=The Commuter reveals the potential of new technology|website=[[The Independent]]|first=Jo|last=Caird|date=22 October 2010|accessdate=23 June 2013}}</ref> In January 2011, Westwick joined [[Clint Eastwood]]'s film ''[[J. Edgar]]'', a biopic about [[J. Edgar Hoover]], the controversial first director of the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2011/01/11/ed-westwick-j-edgar/|title=Ed Westwick cast in 'J. Edgar'|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|first=Margaret|last=Lyons|date=11 January 2011|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref> That same year, he appeared in the romantic comedy ''[[Chalet Girl]]''. He co-narrated the audio book version of ''[[City of Fallen Angels]]'' by [[Cassandra Clare]] and also narrated Clare's second novel ''[[Clockwork Prince]]'' from ''[[The Infernal Devices]]'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2011/12/06/clockwork-prince-cassandra-clare-ed-westwick-interview/|title=EXCLUSIVE: 'Clockwork Prince' Author Cassandra Clare Interviews Audiobook Narrator Ed Westwick|website=[[MTV]]|first=Amy|last=Wilkinson|date=6 December 2011|accessdate=6 December 2011}}</ref> In mid-2011, Westwick became an international celebrity endorser for [[Penshoppe]], a local clothing brand in the [[Philippines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mb.com.ph/node/321192/ed-we|title=Ed Westwick works his 'Chuck Bass' to thrill Manila crowd|website=Manila Bulletin|first=Annie S.|last=Alejo|date=14 June 2011|accessdate=29 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/celeb/fashion/24738/actor-Ed-Westwick-will-be-in-Manila-to-shoot-new-campaign-of-local-clothing-brand|title=Gossip Girl actor Ed Westwick will be in Manila to shoot new campaign of local clothing brand|website=Philippine Entertainment Portal|first=Nerisa|last=Almo|date=28 May 2011|accessdate=29 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307035009/http://www.pep.ph/celeb/fashion/24738/actor-Ed-Westwick-will-be-in-Manila-to-shoot-new-campaign-of-local-clothing-brand|archive-date=7 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe next co-starred in the film adaptation of ''[[Romeo & Juliet (2013 film)|Romeo & Juliet]]'' as the main [[antagonist]] and Juliet's cousin, [[Tybalt]]. The film was released on 11 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/ed-westwick-romeo-and-juliet/92444/|title=Ed Westwick to Play Tybalt in ROMEO AND JULIET|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|first=Adam|last=Chitwood|date=23 May 2011|accessdate=15 January 2012}}</ref> Westwick then portrayed the lead role in the film adaptation of [[Anthony Bourdain]]'s novel ''[[Bone in the Throat]]'', which premiered at [[South by Southwest]] on 14 March 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2013/05/cannes-briefs-wild-bunch-ups-carole-baraton-elle-driver-gets-ugly-studiocanal-selling-100-year-old-man-490792/|title=Ed Westwick Has A 'Bone In The Throat'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=6 May 2013}}</ref> Westwick then co-starred in the horror comedy film ''[[Freaks of Nature (film)|Freaks of Nature]]'', which was released on 30 October 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/movies/column-post/gossip-girl-alum-ed-westwick-may-sink-his-fangs-sonys-kitchen-sink-exclusive-110856|title='Gossip Girl' Alum Ed Westwick in Negotiations to Star in Sony's 'Kitchen Sink' (Exclusive)|website=[[TheWrap]]|first=Jeff|last=Sneider|date=15 August 2013|accessdate=16 September 2013}}</ref> In March 2015, he joined the cast of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s short-lived crime drama series ''[[Wicked City (TV series)|Wicked City]]'' as Kent Grainger, a sadistic Sunset Strip serial killer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/gossip-girl-alum-play-creepy-781019|title='Gossip Girl' Alum to Play Creepy Murderer in ABC Pilot|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Michael|last=O'Connell|date=12 March 2015}}</ref> The series was cancelled after airing 3 episodes, but was picked up by [[Hulu]] to air the remaining 5 episodes. Westwick was next seen in [[Jim Gillespie (director)|Jim Gillespie]]'s ''[[Billionaire Ransom]]'', released on 19 August 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/ed-westwick-dominic-sherwood-join-jim-gillespies-take-down-exclusive-1201181277/|title=Ed Westwick, Dominic Sherwood Join Jim Gillespie's 'Take Down' (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=John|last=Hopewell|date=14 May 2014|accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref> and stars in the thriller ''[[The Crash (2017 film)|The Crash]]'', released on 13 January 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/news/frank-grillo-jekyll-island-minnie-driver-1200775773/|title='The Butler' Producer Sets up Next Pic Starring Frank Grillo and Minnie Driver (EXCLUSIVE)|first=Justin|last=Kroll|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=1 March 2015|date=2013-10-29}}</ref>\n\nWestwick will next star in ''Me, You, Madness'' co-starring and directed by [[Louise Linton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/me-you-madness-first-look-image-of-pic-from-writer-director-star-louise-linton-1202597295/|title=\u2018Me, You, Madness\u2019: First-Look Image Of Pic From Writer-Director-Star Louise Linton|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Erik|last=Pederson|date=April 16, 2019|accessdate=December 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nWestwick was a member of the British band The Filthy Youth.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pressler|first1=Jessica|last2=Rovzar|first2=Chris|url=https://nymag.com/arts/tv/features/46225/|title=The Genius of Gossip Girl|date=21 April 2008|website=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]}}</ref> The [[Punk rock|punk]] band, formed in 2006, was inspired by the [[Rolling Stones]], [[The Doors]] and [[Kings of Leon]]. The songs \"Come Flash All You Ladies\" and \"Orange\" were both featured in an episode of ''Gossip Girl''. The band consisted of fellow countrymen Benjamin Lewis Allingham (guitar), Jimmy Wright (guitar), Tom Bastiani (bass), and John Vooght (drummer). <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1595447/20080923/story.jhtml|title='Gossip Girl' Stars Leighton Meester, Ed Westwick Parlay TV Success Into Music Careers|first=Jocelyn|last=Vena|date=24 September 2008|website=[[MTV]]|accessdate=24 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWestwick shared an apartment with his ''Gossip Girl'' co-star [[Chace Crawford]] in the [[Chelsea, Manhattan|Chelsea]] neighbourhood of [[Manhattan]] from the beginning of the series in 2007 until July 2009, when Crawford moved out.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Leonard|first1=Elizabeth|last2=Garcia|first2=Jennifer|title=Chace Crawford Bachelor No. 1|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20287137,00.html|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=23 June 2013|date=29 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Tartaglione|first=Nancy|title=Chace Crawford Moves Out of Ed Westwick's Apartment|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/chace-crawford-moves-out-of-ed-westwicks-apartment-2009137|website=[[Us Weekly]]|accessdate=23 June 2013|date=13 July 2009}}</ref> He was in a relationship with his Gossip Girl co-star [[Jessica Szohr]] in 2009.<ref>https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/gossip-girl-jessixa-szohr-dating-ed-westwick-can-be-awkward-20092812/</ref> \n\nWestwick supports [[Chelsea F.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/celebs-on-sunday/2009/05/03/ed-westwick-i-can-be-a-real-bitch-people-know-when-to-stay-away-115875-21316088/|title=Ed Westwick: 'I can be a real bitch \u2013 people know when to stay away'|website=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=3 May 2009|accessdate=5 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/funfare/exclusivesarticle.aspx?articleid=693196&publicationsubcategoryid=70|title=Ed Westwick: Television's Most Loved 'Bad Boy'|last=Lo|first=Ricky|website=[[The Philippine Star]]|date=5 June 2011|accessdate=5 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111202020/http://www.philstar.com/funfare/ExclusivesArticle.aspx?articleId=693196&publicationSubCategoryId=70|archive-date=11 November 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Sexual assault claims===\nIn November 2017, allegations were separately made by three women: Kristina Cohen, Rachel Eck, and Aur\u00e9lie Wynn. Cohen and Wynn made claims of  rape, and Eck claims of sexual assault. All three claim the incidents occurred in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ed-westwick-accused-rape-actor-denies-claim-1055474|title='Gossip Girl' Star Ed Westwick Accused of Rape, Actor Denies Claim|date=7 November 2017|last=Gardner|first=Chris|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/ed-westwick-second-accuser-sexual-assault-claim-1202204751/|title=Ed Westwick Calls Rape Accusations \"Provably Untrue\" After Second Woman Comes Forward \u2013 Update|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=Robb|first=David|date=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/11/ed-westwick-third-accuser-sexual-assault-rachel-eck|title=Third Woman Accuses Ed Westwick of Sexual Assault|website=Vanity Fair|last=Bradley|first=Laura|date=15 November 2017}}</ref> Westwick issued a statement describing the allegations from Cohen and Wynn as \"unverified and provably untrue\" and further stated: \"I have never forced myself in any manner, on any woman. I certainly have never committed rape\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/gossip-girl-actor-ed-westwick-accused-of-raping-actress-w511210 |title='Gossip Girl' Actor Ed Westwick Denies Raping Actress Kristina Cohen |last=Chen |first=Joyce |date=7 November 2017 |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/ed-westwick-second-accuser-sexual-assault-claim-1202204751 |title=Second Woman Accuses Ed Westwick Of Sexual Assault |last=Robb |first=David |date=8 November 2017 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/ed-westwick-sexual-assault_us_5a04313ae4b0f76b05c38eb3|title=Second Woman Accuses Actor Ed Westwick Of Sexual Assault|newspaper=[[Huff Post|Huffington Post]]|date=9 November 2017|last1=Dicker|first1=Ron}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/ed-westwick-third-woman-accusations-sexual-assault-1202209295/|title=Third Woman Accuses Ed Westwick Of Sexual Assault|first=David|last=Robb|date=15 November 2017|publisher=|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/mbvd/a-third-woman-says-gossip-girl-star-ed-westwick-sexually|title=A Third Woman Says \"Gossip Girl\" Star Ed Westwick Sexually Assaulted Her|website=BuzzFeed News|date=9 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/ed-westwick-lapd-investigation-rape-allegations-actress-1202203757/|title=LAPD Investigating Rape Allegations Against Ed Westwick|first=David|last=Robb|date=7 November 2017|publisher=|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/ed-westwick-rape-latest-lapd-investigate-kristina-cohen-gossip-girl-a8043176.html|title=Ed Westwick rape allegation 'being investigated by LAPD'|publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=8 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-44985583|title=Ed Westwick will not be prosecuted in US|date=27 July 2018|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com|work=BBC News}}</ref>\nIn July 2018, the office of the Los Angeles District Attorney announced that Westwick would not be prosecuted regarding the claims of rape and sexual assault. Prosecutors said witnesses identified by the first two alleged victims were \"not able to provide information that would enable the prosecution to prove either incident beyond a reasonable doubt\", with prosecutors unable to contact the third claimant. Prosecutors also noted additional claims made by other individuals would not be looked into due to being outside the statute of limitations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-44985583|title=Ed Westwick will not be prosecuted in US|date=27 July 2018|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe allegations resulted in the re-shooting of scenes involving Westwick in the BBC adaptation of the [[Agatha Christie]]'s ''[[Ordeal by Innocence (miniseries)|Ordeal By Innocence]]'' with [[Christian Cooke]], and series two of ''[[White Gold (TV series)|White Gold]]'' being \"paused\". Westwick has stated he is disappointed with the actions of the BBC due to the ongoing investigations, legal processes, and the unverified nature of the claims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-42577505|title=Ed Westwick removed from BBC Agatha Christie drama Ordeal By Innocence|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=5 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/01/05/ed-westwick-replaced-sexual-assault-allegations-ordeal-by-innocence |title=Ed Westwick replaced in Agatha Christie drama following sexual assault claims |last=Romano |first=Nick |date=5 January 2018 |publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/ed-westwick-bbc-ordeal-by-innocence-white-gold-1202205604/ |title=BBC Drops Ed Westwick Drama 'Ordeal By Innocence', Halts Appearance In 'White Gold' |last=Evans |first=Greg |date=10 November 2017 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Children of Men]]''\n| Alex\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Breaking and Entering (film)|Breaking and Entering]]''\n| Zoran\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Son of Rambow]]''\n| Lawrence Carter\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[100 Feet]]''\n| Joey\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[S. Darko]]''\n| Randy Holt\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[McHenry Brothers|The Commuter]]''\n| Bellboy in Lift\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Chalet Girl]]''\n| Jonny Madsen\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[J. Edgar]]''\n| Agent Smith\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Romeo & Juliet (2013 film)|Romeo & Juliet]]''\n| [[Tybalt]]\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Last Flight (film)|Last Flight]]''\n| Charles Gillis\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Bone in the Throat]]''\n| Will Reeves\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Freaks of Nature (film)|Freaks of Nature]]''\n| Milan Pinache\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Billionaire Ransom]]''\n| Billy Speck\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Crash (2017 film)|The Crash]]''\n| Ben Collins\n|\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''Me, You, Madness''\n| Tyler Jones\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]''\n| Holden Edwards\n| Episode: \"Young Mothers Do Have 'Em\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''\n| Johnny Cullin\n| Episode: \"Family Matters\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Afterlife (TV series)|Afterlife]]''\n| Darren\n| Episode: \"Roadside Bouquets\"\n|-\n| 2007\u20132012\n| ''[[Gossip Girl]]''\n| [[Chuck Bass|Charles \"Chuck\" Bass]]\n| Main character; 117 episodes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]''\n| Chris \"Balt\" Smith\n| Episode: \"The Land of Rape and Honey\"\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Wicked City (TV series)|Wicked City]]''\n| Kent Grainger\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Family Guy]]''\n| Football Player / Wedding Officiant (voice)\n| Episode: \"[[The Finer Strings]]\"\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Snatch (TV series)|Snatch]]''\n| Sonny Castillo\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\u20132019\n| ''[[White Gold (TV series)|White Gold]]''\n| Vincent Swan\n| 12 episodes\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Artist\n|-\n| 2018\n| \"Give Me Your Hand\"\n| Himself\n| Shannon K\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2008\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice TV Breakout Star \u2013 Male\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''[[Gossip Girl]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice TV \u2013 Villain|Choice TV \u2013 Villain]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2009\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Young Hollywood Awards]]\n| Young Hollywood Breakthrough \u2013 Male\n| Himself\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Breakthrough Performance \u2013 Male\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''Gossip Girl''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Teen Choice Awards\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Choice TV \u2013 Villain\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2011\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2012\n| [[Teen Choice Award for Choice TV Actor Drama|Choice TV Actor \u2013 Drama]]\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|2067953}}\n* [http://popgurls.com/2007/10/17/popgurls-interview-gossip-girls-ed-westwick-2/ PopGurls Interview: Ed Westwick]\n\n{{Teen Choice Award Choice TV Villain}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Westwick, Ed}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English 